2.0 ACCOUNTING PROCEDURES
2.1 Basis of Accounting
SFA Foundation financial statements are prepared in accordance with the Generally
Accepted Accounting Practices (GAAP).
2.2 Financial Statements
The following statements shall be prepared annually for purposes of external auditing for the
year:
a) Statement of Financial Position.
b) Statement of Comprehensive Income and Expenditures.
c) Statement of Changes in Fund Balances.
d) Statement of Cash Flows.
Accordingly, the audited accounts will be completed by the end of the fourth month of the year
after the financial year end. SFA Foundation financial year will run from January to December.
The principal accounting policies adopted in the preparation of these financial statements are
set out below.
2.2.1 Modified Cash Basis of Accounting
Expenses shall be recognized when incurred and reported in the financial statements in the
period to which they relate. Income shall be recognized when received except for
transactions where other methods are required by law.
2.2.2 Going Concern
It assumes that SFA Foundation will continue to operate indefinitely. On this basis, assets
are recorded based on their original cost net of depreciation and amortization and not on
market value.
2.2.3 Monetary Unit
The business financial transactions recorded and reported should be in monetary unit, such
as US Dollar, GBP, Euro, Kenyan Shilling etc. Thus, any non-financial or non- monetary
information that cannot be measured in a monetary unit are not recorded in the accounting
books, but instead, a memorandum will be used. SFA Foundation’s base accounting currency
shall be the US dollar.
2.2.4 Historical Cost
All business resources acquired should be valued and recorded based on the actual cash
equivalent or original cost of acquisition, not the prevailing market value or future value.
2.2.5 Prudence Concept
This principle states that assets are recognised at the lowest of multiple probable valuations
and liabilities are recognised as soon as they arise.
2.2.6 Consistency
This principle ensures consistency in the accounting procedures used by the business entity
from one accounting period to the next. It allows fair comparison of financial information
between two accounting periods. This does not mean that a change in method cannot be
made, but if a change is made it will be identified and the effect on the reported results fully
disclosed in accordance with International Financial Reporting Standards (IFRS).
2.2.7 Materiality
Ideally, business transactions that may affect the decision of a user of financial information
are considered important or material, thus, must be reported properly. This principle allows
errors or violations of accounting valuation involving immaterial and small amount of recorded
business transaction.
