2.4 Record Keeping
SFA Foundation is required to maintain all documents relating to the different programmes
that it runs, and to make such documents available to stakeholders who include the donors,
internal staff and auditors. Finance documents contain sensitive and confidential information.
Consequently, the records must be in the custody of only those persons who are directly
involved in the finance and accounting responsibilities. Other persons may access the records
only with the prior authorization of the Head of Finance and Grants/equivalent or his/her
designee. The accounting records must be properly and securely kept to protect them from
accidental or malicious damage. The Head of Finance and Grants/equivalent has the
responsibility to enforce thisregulation.
The finance department must keep accurate and up-to-date records and documents in
respect of all resources received and any expenditure incurred with the funds made available
to ensure that all expenditures are in conformity with provisions of the project work plan and
budgets.
For each resource received or disbursement, proper supporting documentation shall be
maintained, including original invoices, utility bills and receipts relating to transactions.
SFA Foundation financial transactions are subjected to the scrutiny of external/internal
auditors. It is therefore important that adequate records and supporting documents are kept to
prove the accuracy of the costs reported in the accounts in respect of each financial
transaction, and also to show that the appropriate rules and procedures have been followed.
All documents in support of payments shall be retained by SFA Foundation for a minimum of
seven (7) years from the date of payment or longer, should this be required by funders. This
will ensure compliance with local law requirements. If there are on-going checks, reviews,
