3.0 INTERNAL CONTROL
3.1 Internal Control Environment
The SFA Foundation internal financial control system is designed to provide reasonable
assurance on the following:
a) Effectiveness, efficiency, and economy of operations
b) Reliability of reporting
c) Safeguarding of assets and information
d) Prevention, detection, correction and follow‑up on fraud and irregularities
e) Adequate management of the risks relating to the legality and regularity of the underlying
transactions, considering the multiannual character of programmes as well as the nature
of the payments concerned
The SFA Foundation financial control system includes the following:
a) Segregation of duties
b) Financial Risk management system
c) Management of conflict of interests as relates to Finance and relatedprocedures.
d) Adequate audit trails
3.1.1 Segregation of duties
Adequate segregation of duties reduces the likelihood that mistakes or inappropriate actions
will remain undetected by increasing the element of internal checking.
At SFA Foundation, where practical and cost effective, no one person will have sole control
over the lifespan of a transaction; no one person should be able to initiate, record, authorize
and reconcile a transaction.
At SFA Foundation, segregation takes place at various levels:
 Segregation of function: where practical, the following key functions are segregated:
carrying out of a transaction, recording that transaction in the accounting records and
maintaining custody of assets that arise from the transaction
 Accounting operations, where practical, are segregated. For example, if the bank
payments are done by Finance Officer; then the monthly bank reconciliation statements
must be prepared by a different person within the finance department and the bank
reconciliation to be approved by a senior employee.
 There shall be segregation of duties and responsibilities in the procurement and payment
processes.
3.1.2 Financial Risk Management System
The SFA Foundation overall risk register is maintained by the Head of Legal and
Compliance/equivalent. However, the Financial Risk Management Register is maintained by
the Head of Finance and Grants/equivalent and serves as a central repository for any related
Financial and Accounting related risk information. The Register is reviewed every quarter
and compiled and presented to the EMT and the SFA Foundation Board for review of action
points. Its main purpose is to provide SFA Foundation management, staff and any authorized
external parties information on the main risks faced by the organization. It is used as the main
tool for managing and mitigating the risks identified. The SFA Foundation risk register
provides information on the following:
a) Who is responsible for managing each identified risk (risk owner);
b) Risks identified in terms of likelihood of occurrence and impact if it doesoccur.
c) A grading of each risk according to a risk assessment table
d) An outline of the proposed mitigation plan (preventative andcontingency).
