3.1.3 Management of Conflict of Interests
All staff are expected to have signed the Code of Conduct which contains the standards that
govern conflict of Interest. All Staff are expected to follow the highest standards of honesty
and fairness. All known or potential conflicts of interest shall be disclosed immediately to the
Head of Human Resources and Operations and their supervisor for action and recording.
SFA Foundation staff shall not take any action which may bring their own interests into conflict
with those of SFA Foundation. Where such a risk exists, the person in question shall refrain
from taking part and shall refer the matter to the Head of Human Resources and Operations
who shall confirm in writing whether a conflict of interest exists. The person in question shall
also inform his or her superior. Where a conflict of interest is found to exist, the person in
question shall cease all activities in thematter.
SFA Foundation employees have a responsibility when procuring goods and services on
behalf of SFA Foundation, to do so in an ethical and professional manner, and for the benefit
of SFA Foundation. The policies that apply include:
a) Employees shall not accept gifts, entertainment, meals, travel, and any other benefits or
favours from suppliers with whom SFA Foundation does or may do business, except as
token courtesies or except on behalf of SFA Foundation and for SFA Foundation’s
benefit. To ensure transparency and fairness and to avoid conflict of interest, gifts, benefits
or favours received from SFA Foundation suppliers shall be declared to the Head of
Human Resources and Operations
b) Employees shall disclose suppliers they have a conflict with (or they think they may have a
conflict with) to the Head of Finance and Grants for approval before the purchase
c) SFA Foundation employees shall not take any steps to influence the acquisition of goods
or services from an entity he/she owns or in which their families have a financial interest
in, or may directly benefit from such purchase
3.1.4 Adequate audit trails
The objective is to maintain adequate accounting records and other supporting documents,
which provide a complete history for each financial transaction, to prove the accuracy of the
costs reported in the accounts in respect of each accounting transaction, and also to show
that the appropriate policies and procedures have been followed.
All accounting transaction documents supporting payments must be retained by SFA
Foundation for a minimum of seven (7) years from the date of payment. If there are on-going
checks, reviews, audits, investigations, litigation or other pursuits, the records and other
supporting documentation must be retained until the end of theseprocedures.
