5.0 REVENUE AND ACCOUNTS RECEIVABLE
5.1 Recognition of Revenue
Revenue is recognized when it is received. SFA Foundation has two primary sources of
income, grant income and operational income to be earned from interest from short-term
investments, indirect recoveries from grants, SFA Foundation, investments and business
sources.
5.2 Receipting of Revenue
The objective of a receipting system is to ensure that all funds donated/collected are fully
accounted for in financial records and reported to the funders.
To ensure that funds are fully accounted for in financial records, the following strategies will
be applied:
a) Effective control of accounting documents (receipt books, chequebooks);
b) All receipts must be processed in the finance system and a receipt will be issued from
the Finance Management System in two (2) copies one to be given to the Organization or
Individual who issued the funds;
c) All documents will be systematically digitized for all audits.
5.3 Grants Receivables
This refers to funds to be received from funders through an award. Grants receivables is
categorised in several ways
5.3.1 Unrestricted Funds
These are funds originating from sources that have no specification as to the use of the funds.
These funds do not have to be allocated to specific projects and can be used for general
operating expenses of SFA Foundation.
5.3.2 Restricted funds
These are funds that have a specific purpose attached to them from the funding source. They
must be used in compliance with the wishes and directions from the funding source, whether
it is a donor or an agency providing funds for a specific project.
Accounts receivable for restricted or unrestricted grants from donors are recognized and
recorded when the amount of the pledge is known, and award letter received.
5.4 In-kind contributions
These are non-cash donations of goods or services. It is critical when documenting in- kind
contributions that both the donation as well as the value is recorded. Before accounting for
the in-kind contribution, one of the two criteria below must bemet;
a) The service must create a non-financial benefit; or the services must require specialized
skills;
b) Would typically have been purchased by the organization.
If either of these conditions is met then the organization must record as an in-kind
contribution, the value of the goods/services. The value of the contribution should be
determined based on fair market value of the good or service being provided. The following
must be properly documented:
a) Date and location of the contribution
b) Detailed description of item/service
c) Estimated value of contribution
d) How the value was determined
e) Who made the determination?
f) Was the contribution obtained with Government funds?
g) Name and signature of the contributor
