8.0 ASSET MANAGEMENT
8.1 Investments
8.1.1 Investment Objective
Operating funds should not be allowed to remain unproductive for more than two (2) months.
Cash should be invested in such a manner as to be readily available and to earn a
reasonable return without jeopardizing SFA Foundation assets and funders regulations
where excess funding is related to grants. For the safe custody of surpluses as well as
operating funds, the Executive Management Team shall act as an investment committee to
oversee the SFA Foundation investment portfolio, the EMT shall inform the FRA committee
on short-term investments made. As a means of guiding the investment process, the
following considerations should beconsidered:
a) What is the investment objective?
b) How much risk is SFA Foundation prepared to take?
c) What types of investments will be permitted?
d) How much diversification of investment funds will be permitted?
See the SFA Foundation Investment Policy and Procedures for more details
8.1.2 Reserve Fund
SFA Foundation aims to build a reserve fund. The purpose of the Reserve Fund is to ensure’
future stability and capability of providing services for its key operational costs. The
Restricted Reserve Fund consists of assets segregated as the “restricted funds” on the SFA
Foundation balance sheet and separate from those necessary to the management and
operations of the organization. It is intended to maintain a Restricted Reserve Fund equal to
approximately 3-months’ worth of cash for operations (or an average of 25% of the operating
budget). The Reserve Fund will normally only be utilized in extraordinary circumstances as
authorized by the FRA committee of the Board. As operating surpluses permit, it is the goal
of the SFA Foundation Board to increase the Restricted Reserve Fund to approximately 6-
months’ worth of cash operations (or an average of 50% of the budget).
Over time, it is the intent to build a Strategic Reserve equal to a set dollar value. The purpose
of the Strategic Reserve would be to allow the Board the flexibility to approve special projects
that were not previously planned for during the approval of the budget. SFA Foundation Board
approval is required to access any of the various reserve funds.
8.2 Capital Equipment
8.2.1 Capitalization Policy
Only capital equipment with an acquisition cost of more than USD 2,000 individually or in
aggregate shall be capitalized. This threshold shall be reviewed from time to time based on
prevailing circumstances relevant to SFA Foundation.
8.2.2 Budgeting for Capital Assets (See section 4 above)
The Head of Finance and Grants/equivalent in consultation with budget holders will, before
the start of every financial year, ensure that asset acquisition budget is prepared, listing
the assets to be procured during the financial year to meet the needs of the various
departments within SFA Foundation. The budget is then reviewed by the Head of Finance
and Grants before being sent to the ED and the ExecutiveManagement Team
8.2.3 Control over Fixed Assets
An Asset register is established with an entry or record sheetfor each item. Each asset should
be tagged with a unique reference number for identification purposes. The Fixed assets
register is reconciled annually to the General Ledger since the Net Book Value must appear
in the financial statements. Assets are physically verified annually. Major assets that are still
in good condition are all insured, and the insurable value reviewed every two years to
ensure the insurance cover remains adequate. Refer to SFA Foundation Procurement
Guidelines and Procedures for guidance.
