8.2.5 Disposals Policy
The policy aims to achieve the best possible outcome for SFA Foundation by gaining the best
available net return when selling and to ensure SFA Foundation is even-handed, open and
honest in all dealings. The disposal policy should be read in collaboration with the
Procurement policy on asset disposal. The best value outcome to SFA Foundation must be
a major consideration when disposing of assets. All disposals shall be handled through the
Asset Disposals Committee, which for the time being is the Procurement Committee and is
an adhoc committee. The final decision to dispose of assets must be approved by the
Executive Director/equivalent following recommendations from the HOF. Priority shall be
given to staff.
Long-term assets under SFA Foundation may be disposed for various reasons including.
a) They may no longer be required
b) They may no longer be suitable for use within the operations of SFA Foundation. This
may be due to various reasons such as the availability of new and more efficient
technology or simply age
c) They may no longer exist as they may have been lost or stolen
d) They are required to be disposed of under a particular policy e.g., motorvehicle
e) Occupying storage space and not being needed in the foreseeablefuture
f) Reaching their optimum selling time to maximize returns
g) No longer complying with occupational health and safetystandards
h) Found to contain hazardous materials
i) Beyond repair but able to be sold for scrap
When an asset is no longer required by SFA Foundation, it is disposed using any of the
prescribed disposal methods.
Lost or stolen assets must be reported at the earliest reasonable opportunity. It is the
responsibility of the staff to which any Property Plant and Equipment (PPE) has been
allocated to report any loss of the same. Any loss must be reported to the Head of Finance
and Grants and the immediate supervisor. The officer responsible for insurance must
also be informed. Whenever possible, the police should also be informed, and a crime
number/report be given to the member of staff who has lost the asset/or from whom the
asset has been stolen. These details should be passed to the officer responsible for
insurance. If the asset is not recovered details of the loss and any insurance receipt should
be forwarded to the Head of Finance and Grants. All disposal of assets must be recorded
promptly in the books of SFA Foundation.
The carrying amount of an item of an Asset shall be written off on disposal or when
scrapped, that is, there are no future economic benefits expected from its use or disposal.
Gains or losses arising from the writing off of an item of PPE shall be included in “Other
Income” in the year in which the item is derecognized. The gains or losses arising from the
writing off of an asset shall be determined as the difference between the net disposal
proceeds, if any, and the carrying amount of the item.
Asset disposal decisions, and the reasons for taking them, should be documented. Not only
does this assist in audit and other examinations, but it highlights successes and problems
for future reference.
