6.0 TRAVEL PLANNING AND AUTHORIZATION
6.1 Yearly and or Quarterly travel plan
All work-related travel, regardless of type and source of funding, must be incorporated in a yearly
travel plan, and subsequently, in the departmental annual procurement plan. Where the travel is
not known, there is the option of presenting on best estimate at the start of a quarter and budget
to the best extent possible.
6.2 Travel not in the approved travel plan
International travel that is not part of the approved travel plan can be taken if funds are available
and if the travel is approved as per the travel approval procedure.
6.3 Employee Group Travel
As a general guideline, senior staff should avoid traveling together. If the travel cannot be avoided,
they should travel on different flights whether it is local or international travel. It is understood that
there will be times when this is unavoidable.
The number of SFA Foundation personnel traveling together on the same flight should not exceed
five for security and safety reasons. Any deviation of this policy will require approval from the
Executive Director or his/her designate.
When situations arise that are impossible to avoid a high number of SFA Foundation staff
travelling together, extra insurance must be included when requesting for the ticket.
6.4 Emergency travel
It may occur that an employee must travel but may be unable to obtain Travel Authorization (TA)
approval from their supervisor before issuance of a ticket or departure. The traveller should
attempt to find a valid signature (e.g. in the case of his/her supervisor being absent, the Unit head,
Head of Finance and Grants or Executive Director may sign on behalf of the supervisor). If that is
not possible, the ticket will be charged to the personal account of the employee pending the
approval (by email or by signature) of a valid approver. It is understood by all that such a
procedure should remain exceptional.
6.5 Travel Authorization (TA)
a) A TA is required for all travel (local and international, and all transport methods) undertaken
by SFA Foundation staff or for which SFA Foundation pays (e.g. SFA Foundation sends
prepaid tickets to workshop participants or a consultant);
b) The TA must be approved by the budget holder or his designee and submitted to the Finance
Department as soon as the travel is confirmed. It must however be not less than Three weeks
(21 days) before the trip to ensure flexibility in making travel arrangements and to obtain the
lowest appropriate cost. While there may be circumstances necessitating urgent travel, SFA
Foundation staff must make all efforts to comply with this provision. In cases where the 21
days’ advance notice is not met, a justification from the traveller’s supervisor must accompany
the TA for approval by the Head of Finance. In cases where a TA is requesting travel less
than five days before departure, a justification from the unit Head or Director must accompany
the TA for approval by the Executive Director;
c) All required information – routing, estimated cost, requested advance amount, travel dates, –
should be provided on the TA for the signing authority’s guidance. The procurement unit, the
travel and Events officer and/or the relevant Programme Assistants designated to work with
the travel agent may assist in finding out costs for particular routes;
d) The Procurement office will ensure the travel agencies have received signed local purchase
orders (LPOs) before they issue airline tickets;
Page 4 of 14
e) All travel must be approved in advance by an authorized signatory except as indicated above
for emergency cases.
6.6 Role of Finance in reviewing the TA’s
The finance department is involved in the reviewing the TAs as follows:
a) When a travel advance is requested, and a payment needs to be initiated, the role of the
Finance Unit involves verifying the reasonableness of the request as per section 8.1 on travel
advances below;
b) After verification that funds are available, the Finance department signs the TA and approves
the LPO.
6.7 Car rentals
As with all expenditures, car rentals should be used only when the efficient conduct of company
business precludes the use of other means of transportation. For example, a car rental would not
be justified from the airport to a hotel, if shuttle or cab service were available. Justification for use
of Car Rental needs to be made if it is the most economical means of movement and authorization
given by the Unit Head. The traveller should strive to make all arrangements through the travel
agency or its global network. The rented car should be no more than a regular passenger saloon
vehicle. The use of car rental should be pre-approved before travel by the appropriate Head of
Department.
6.8 Use of office/taxi services
Staff members should be able to apply for and obtain office transport or be authorized by the
Head of Finance and Grants to use a taxi service upon authorization by the immediate supervisor.
When a staff member needs transport during office hours for official purpose, he/she should fill
out a transport request in the book maintained at the front desk officer or his/her alternate
designate at the earliest opportunity. The request should be submitted before the end of the
preceding day if transport is required early the next morning or before 10 a.m. if it is required for
the afternoon of the same day.
If a long trip is involved, then requests should come in as soon as the details of the trip are known,
and at least three working days before the intended trip so that adequate arrangements can be
made. No transport requests should be made directly to the driver(s) unless prior arrangements
have been made with the administrative office.
6.9 Use of personal vehicle
In the event that office transport is not available and the use of a personal vehicle for official
business is authorized by the Head of Human Resources and Operations (HRO), depending on
the reasonableness of the request, then the staff member can claim reimbursement of expenses
on the basis of a mileage rate equivalent to what Automobile Association (AA) Kenya, or similar
local agency has published to cover fuel costs, wear and tear and insurance costs. There will be
no further liability on the part of SFA Foundation in the event of any accident or loss while the
personal vehicle is used for official business.
