7.0 STAFF TRAVELING TO SFA FOUNDATION PROGRAM SITES
7.1 Hotel arrangements
Standard hotel rates will be negotiated by the procurement unit and the contracted travel agency
and circulated in the first quarter of each year. Staff should contact the Program Assistants who
would be equipped with this knowledge to make hotel arrangements when traveling. Frequently
travelling staff will be issued with debit cards for travel only on rare occasions will staff need to
carry sufficient funds for their hotel payments.
7.2 Travel insurance
All regular and short-term staff will receive travel insurance as and when there is need, this need
will be evaluated on a case by case basis as mentioned on the SFA Foundation Risk Management
Policy. This will be issued at least two days before travel. Travellers are advised to be familiar
with the Travel insurance policy and the emergency procedures to follow when on travel. When it
is deemed necessary for the travel insurance, the Travel and Events Officer or designated
program assistants are responsible for obtaining the travel insurance from the travel agent.
7.3 Combining Business and Personal Travel
a) If a routing is modified from “most direct” to any alternate route for personal reasons (i.e.,
when the traveller travels to a location not related to the official purpose of the trip), any
additional cost, as calculated by the SFA Foundation travel agent, will be charged to the
personal account of the traveller;
b) The same principle would apply if a traveller stays at a destination longer than necessary for
any other reason other than the purpose of SFA Foundation business. The difference in price,
if any, will be borne by the traveller;
c) A spouse or other individual may accompany an employee on a business trip at the
employee’s expense, if their travel expenses are paid for separately, not charged to SFA
Foundation, and do not require any SFA Foundation employee or the travel agency to
complete additional work.
7.4 Travel Report
All travellers must prepare a travel report. This report should be submitted to the relevant
manager who approved the travel assignment. It will give the objectives of the trip and their
achievement and what action plans will be taken out of the activity that was accomplished by the
report. It will be given within 10 working days of their return to the duty station. No additional travel
should be approved by the supervisor until the travel report is submitted unless the traveller is
required to travel again within 10 working days.
