10.3 Routing and carrier preferences
The routing for any trip shall be the most direct available. “Most direct” is not always a geographic
condition; it can be an economic condition, but in some cases, it may not be the most economical
– in such cases, the most direct is the routing which produces the lowest applicable ticket cost
will apply (e.g. Rome- Nairobi through either Amsterdam or London). The instruction to the SFA
Foundation travel agents is that the most direct routing should be recommended to a traveller by
way of a suggested itinerary. However, for carrier selection, the most important single criterion is
safety, and the SFA Foundation travel agents will not recommend flights on carriers that are
known to have poor safety records.
Travellers, however, may express their preference for a specific routing and explain that in the
TA. Factors that could justify not using the most direct routing are:
• Longer transit time;
• Required change of airports;
• Level of security of airport;
• Later departure or earlier arrival;
10.4 Security for International travel
The staff travelling should ensure that they:
a) Maintain up-to-date pre-departure briefing materials with the host institution emergencycontact information;
b) Receive security briefings that include: the current security situation, recent incidents,
emergency contact information, security guidance, and any restrictions on movement or
behaviour. This material should be forwarded to the traveller prior to his/her departure from
the Programme Assistants as provided by travel agents;
c) Educate yourself about the destination country, country office programs, and safety, security,
and health issues;
d) Ensure that the name and location of the Hotel or Office to be visited is known and informed
before travel;
e) Have in your possession an international identification documents;
f) Photocopy of your passport and visa, credit cards, and other documents that would need to
be replaced quickly if lost or stolen; leave one set of copies with a reliable person at home
and carry extra copies in places separate from originals;
g) Know the location and contact information for your destination site (country office, conference
center, etc.) and for your consulate or embassy at the country of destination; carry this and all
other important personal information;
h) Leave a copy of itinerary and contact information with the host Institution and call or e-mail
your office and home to confirm safe arrival;
i) Abide by all host Institution safety and security policies and procedures.
10.5 Other
10.5.1 Traveller Profiles
This is in the employee’s interest as it will ensure that the reservations are made as per the
traveller’s preferences (e.g. seat assignment, online check-in, dietary constraints, airport
transfers).
The employee is responsible for informing the travel & event office of all personal travel
information requirements, such as cell phone numbers, titles, medical restrictions, residence,
meal requirements and seating preferences.
