10.6 Airline Frequent Flyer Programs
Travellers may retain frequent flyer program benefits for business or personal usage. Frequent
flyer programs should not influence the choice of carrier. Employees whose selection is biased
on that basis may be asked to pay the difference between the most logical choice based on
schedule, airline safety and the price of the actual ticket they chose.
SFA Foundation will not reimburse travellers for tickets purchased with frequent flyer miles.
10.7 Layovers
When layover time exceeds eight hours, staff members on mission travel may be entitled to a
day room if reasonable accommodation can be found in the airport or within its vicinity. For
layovers of less than eight hours but longer than three hours, travellers can pay for access to
airport lounges and claim the cost on their expense reports. If the layover is known beforehand,
approval should be sort before travel from the budget holder and the Head of Finance and Grants.
10.8 Delays/Forced Layovers
Should an airline delay necessitate an overnight stay, the traveller should first attempt to secure
complimentary lodging from the airline before arranging lodging on their own, subject to hotel and
other maximum daily rate for that location. However, where a traveller is late to arrive at the
airport and finds their airline departed, they would not be entitled to the benefit if it is not offered
on complementary basis.
10.9 Heavy or excess Baggage
If the traveller is transporting documents or other items relating to SFA Foundation business of
such a weight that excess baggage is charged by the airline, the expense will be reimbursed. SFA
Foundation will not reimburse for personal excess baggage.
The travel agency may also be able to arrange baggage allowances if requested in advance. Staff
members should not hesitate to ask them to arrange for that.
10.10 Visas
For all authorized business travel, requests for assistance should be directed to the travel office
and Program Assistants. Staff members are requested to give sufficient time (at least a month) to
allow for proper visa arrangements without disrupting the flow of requests made by other staff
members. This may be shorter depending on the embassy process. Visa requirements are sent
together with the travel itinerary. Travellers should note, however, that embassies are increasingly
requiring the physical presence of the traveller before they can issue the visa.
For re-entry visas for Kenya (i.e. multiple entries) for frequent travellers, a minimum of five working
days to a month is required by the Protocol Assistant to allow for the processing of the request by
the Protocol Office.
10.11 Inoculations
SFA Foundation reimburses fully for inoculations and prophylactic medicines required or
recommended for staff and legal or known dependents at duty stations and for all staff during
official travel. It is the responsibility of the travelling staff to ensure that they know which
inoculations and prophylactic medicines are required and the time period required before travel
to avoid any disappointments. Please note that you are covered under the medical insurance for
travel vaccines upto a maximum of USD 150
Page 14 of 14
10.12 Extended travel
For travel of an exceptional duration, such as when an individual may be assigned to work with
or train at a collaborating organization for several weeks or even months, different arrangements
to cover living expenses may be applied if it is clear that lower costs for subsistence will be
incurred (such as if the traveller is staying in a serviced hotel room with kitchen facilities, etc.). In
such a case the usual country daily rate will not be in effect. Such circumstances should be
discussed with the finance office and line manager as soon as plans are developed for the travel,
either during the budgeting process but definitely at least one month in advance of the actual
travel itself.
