1. INTRODUCTION
This manual is a human resource policies and administrative procedures guidebook for use by
staff of the Science for Africa Foundation (SFA). It communicates the Foundation’s policies
efficiently and effectively and eases the administrative burden on supervisory personnel. It
establishes how SFA adapts to change in the work environment. It has been prepared with
reference to Kenya’s Employment Laws and Regulations and in consultation with the staff of the
Foundation, and should be read in conjunction with other SFA Policy documents such the AntiFraud Bribery policy etc.
SFA believes that team effort can best be carried out within the framework of a sound, equitable
human resources program that will result in harmonious employee-employer relationships. SFA
strives to employ capable, well-qualified, and industrious employees who will accept the
responsibilities of their positions and perform their services in a courteous and efficient manner.
In exchange, SFA seeks to establish suitable working conditions based upon equitable and
reasonable standards that make SFA a great place to work.
It is important for employees of the Foundation, to know the policies and benefit packages
available to them. This manual not only outlines the policy towards the various phases of
employee-employer relationships but also indicates the manner in which the policy will be
administered. The regulations may be supplemented or amended by the Management and
subsequently approved by the SFA Board without prejudice to the acquired rights of staff
members, having regard to total contractual benefits. SFA therefore reserves the right to make
amendments to this handbook.
The Foundation has an open door policy. Employees are encouraged to raise any concerns or
recommendations relating to improvement of the Foundation’s manual or service delivery.
Employees are further welcome to consult with each other and management, at all times. SFA
strives to work as a team and strengthen its team building efforts. SFA therefore wants its
employees to feel and be part of the team.
If the legal rights of employees of the Foundation should exceed those contained herein through
change of Kenyan employment law, the Kenyan laws will prevail.
1.2 Scope and Purpose of this Manual
It is the desire of the Foundation to establish conditions of employment that are recognised
clearly as being fair to the interests of those concerned and that encourages staff to take a
sincere interest and pride in the Foundation and its programme of work, and to exert their
best talents and efforts in the discharge of their duties and responsibilities.
These HRPPM policies are applicable to the staff of SFA. They do not apply to short-term
staff on assignment to the SFA, consultants, and other categories of temporary staff. These
staff are governed by their individual contracts of employment with their employers. The
purpose of this Policies and Procedures Manual (PPM) is to establish a firm base from which
the Foundation can manage its personnel affairs efficiently and with due regard to the
complexities of its operations and the individuality of its staff.
The policies seek to ensure continued success in achieving SFA’s mission through highlydiverse, qualified, motivated, and professionally-skilled individuals whose support to
programs and administration contributes to the overall success of the organisation. They also
seek to match the jobs available with the right skills needed to perform them effectively and
efficiently; maintain gender and diversity balance; and motivate staff, inspire Innovation and
creativity, manage change, and improve productivity and morale. Accordingly, SFA’s HR
policies enable it to employ, develop, and retain staff members that meet high standards of
competence, efficiency, and integrity.
1.3 Amendment and Review
SFA management reserves the right, based on changing conditions and/or other
considerations, to modify, revoke, suspend, or terminate any or all of these policies, fully or
in part, at any time, with or without notice. Such modifications, revocations, suspensions,
terminations or changes, are subject to the approval of the Management and the Board
Members. These policies and procedures manual may be reviewed periodically and
adjustments incorporated, as the Executive Director and the Senior Management deem them
advisable.
When the interests of SFA so require, Management may make individual exceptions to the
provisions of the Manual, provided that such exceptions are not inconsistent with the
regulations and that they are agreed to by the staff members directly affected and are, in the
opinion of Management, not prejudicial to the interest of any other staff member or group of
staff members. Such exceptions will be done in writing and the Executive Director will inform
the board during the next meeting.
All deletions, additions, and modifications will be circulated to all staff and to those responsible
for the implementation and administration of these policies, in numbered and dated memos
signed by the Executive Director, or as delegated. Such numbered memoranda should be
filed with this document and the appropriate note of the change made in the referred-to policy
or procedure. Questions from staff members on policy interpretation, application and
procedures should be addressed to the Head Human Resources.
2. GENERAL POLICIES AND PROCEDURES
2.1 Definitions
Departmental Heads
For the purpose of this Human Resources and Procedure Manual (HRPM) departmental
heads, unless otherwise indicated by the context, includes other officers of corresponding
rank, having operational responsibility for the organizational unit.
Duty Station
Duty station is the geographic location, headquarters or outreach station to which a staff
member is assigned.
Staff Association
A staff association is a voluntary, free, non-political association of staff members formed to
further the interests and objectives of SFA and maintain work standards, staff morale and
interests in conformity with the terms and conditions of service. SFA would recognize the
formation of such associations.
Management Team
“Management Team” is a team of proactive people who are responsible for planning and
controlling assigned SFA resources to achieve its mandate and objectives.
Delegation of Authority
When responsibility for approval is specified as the “Executive Director”, only the Executive
Director or (in the Executive Director’s absence) the SFA official designated as the Officer in
Charge may approve. When approval is by “the Executive Director or his designate”, the
Executive Director may issue, as an internal SFA Memorandum, a list of others who may
approve various categories of actions.
Dependants
Authorized dependants are the legal spouse or a domestic partner of the employee, and
unmarried, natural, or legally adopted children until their 24th birthday. A person may be
designated as a domestic partner if she/he has been living with the employee for at least two
years, and a declaration of Domestic Partnership form has been executed and accepted by
SFA.
To be eligible for the educational grant, dependent children must be under 24 years of age.
Handicapped natural children of any age residing with the employee are also considered to
be authorized dependants.
However, for purposes of medical insurance, the definition of dependant follows the
provisions of the contract between SFA’s agent and the group insurer.
Entitlements
Entitlements are provisions that grant perquisites to a staff member and his/her authorized
dependants. Entitlements, whether in cash or in kind, cannot be transferred to another
individual nor converted to another entitlement or cash unless specifically allowed in the policy
statement granting each specific entitlement, e.g., the home leave/ entitlement for NonKenyans which is customarily converted to a cash payment to the vendors or reimbursed to
staff upon satisfactory submission of supporting documents.
Temporary Staff
Temporary staff and consultants are not full-time regular staff of SFA. They are hired to
complete a specific task or activities limited in time and scope; and are not appointed through
the recruitment procedures.
Base Salary
Base salary is that part of total compensation, exclusive of all other payments in cash or kind
for allowances, benefits and entitlements that is paid in cash to the employee for the work
performed for SFA.
Application of this Manual
• The provisions of this Human Resources Policies and Procedures Manual (HRPPM)
shall be applied without regard to gender, race, national or social origin, religion,
political affiliation or any other form of personal identity, to all regular staff across all
SFA offices holding indefinite or fixed-term appointments of one year or more.
• Other personnel appointed on a temporary or part-time basis shall be subject to the
provisions of this manual and must be specified in their contract of employment.
• Entitlement to benefits is not automatic but directly related to the staff member’s
individual circumstances.
• Unless specifically permitted in a stipulated human resources policy, entitlements set
forth in this manual may not be accumulated, transferred to another individual,
converted to or added to another entitlement or paid in cash or in kind. An entitlement
that is not used as explained in this manual therefore is lost and cannot be reclaimed.
• Under unusual circumstances, the Executive Director with the knowledge and written
authorization of the Management may make exceptions to these policies and/or their
application.
• SFA’s policies and procedures are subject to the limitations of agreements with, as
well as the laws and custom of countries within whose borders SFA operates. SFA
is also subject to the contract, provisions and funding decisions of donors. Therefore
SFA’s Board and Management reserve the right to act on such considerations and
change, suspend or terminate any of its policies and procedures as deemed
necessary.
• It is the staff member’s duty to report changes in individual and/or family circumstances
to the Foundation as soon as possible. Such changes may include: marriage,
separation, divorce, birth or death of dependants, etc.
2.2 Equal Employment Opportunity
SFA is an "equal opportunity employer," committed to making staff appointments regardless
of social origin, age, citizenship, ethnic and/or racial background, disability, marital status,
national origin, religion, personal appearance, family responsibilities, political affiliation,
sexual orientation, gender identity and expression, and genetic information or any other basis
prohibited by the Laws of Kenya. Additionally, the SFA will use good faith efforts to achieve
ethnic and gender diversity throughout the workforce.
In determining its employment conditions, SFA endeavours to establish conditions that are
competitive within comparable labour markets from which SFA draws its staff. SFA is
committed to establishing and maintaining a work environment that fosters productive
working relationships and mutual respect among its staff.
This policy applies to all terms and conditions of employment including hiring, training,
promotion, performance evaluation, compensation and termination. This policy also prohibits
harassment in the workplace based on any of the above listed characteristics. Impermissible
harassment can be either verbal or physical conduct which disrupts or interferes with another
employee's work performance or which creates an intimidating, offensive, or hostile work
environment.
Any staff member who believes that a violation of these policies has occurred should bring
such violation to the attention of the Executive Director (ED) who will ensure that SFA
investigates the complaint and remedies any violation found to have occurred. Retaliation
against an individual staff member who reports a violation of the Equal Employment
Opportunity or Harassment Policy or provides information in connection with any such matter
will not be tolerated by SFA, and will itself be grounds for disciplinary action.
2.3 Code of Conduct
SFA employees are expected to behave in a professional, business-like manner at work, on
SFA premises, and whenever representing the SFA. Employees are accountable for
behaviour outside of work that has a negative impact on the individual's ability to perform
his/her responsibilities at work.
To avoid damage to the integrity of SFA or its employees, and to protect the rights of
employees, families, and the public, SFA has established guidelines concerning professional
conduct of employees. This Code aims to foster and maintain public trust and confidence in
the integrity and professionalism of SFA by ensuring that employees:
• Maintain appropriate standards of conduct
• Develop those skills necessary for the efficient performance of their duties
• Maintain fairness in decision making
• Maintain and enhance the reputation of SFA
• Adhere to appropriate ethical standards
The personal and professional behaviour of SFA employees should conform to the
standards that reasonably could be expected of persons in such positions. This includes:
• A commitment by employees to professional standards in promoting and actualising
the goals and objectives of SFA
• A commitment to the ethics principles defined within the code
• The promotion of the rights of employees of SFA
• Conduct which is professional and which has regard to SFA’s interests and policies;
• Conduct which will not compromise either the employee’s position or that of SFA;
• A commitment that the SFA will be regarded as the focal point of the professional life
of employees;
• The promotion of an environment that supports the pursuit of knowledge, personal and
career development;
• Maintain a SFAe and healthy work environment;
• Ensure a work environment that respects the dignity of the individual and that is free
of all forms of bullying, discrimination, harassment and abuse of power;
• Be responsible to the Executive Director and other SFA authority in the exercise of
their functions and respecting lines of authority;
• Treat all colleagues and partners with personal and professional respect and courtesy,
exercising sensitivity to their social and cultural beliefs, rights, duties and aspirations;
• Respect the property of SFA, using it economically and only for official purposes;
• Avoid activities and making public announcements incompatible with their duties at
SFA or detrimental to SFA's interests;
• Respect personal and professional confidentiality, and exercise discretion in all
matters of official business;
• Act responsibly in all e-communications e.g. internet and web-based activities;
• Be willing to discuss and manage conflict in an open manner with a goal of reaching
resolution whenever involved in a dispute;
• Respect the laws and customs of the country in which they are working; and,
• Employees’ requirement to abide by the Anti-Fraud and bribery policy and Conflict of
Interest Policy. Employees (including managers) must ensure their conduct
contributes to a workforce that is free from harassment and discrimination.
In accepting an appointment to SFA, staff members signify their intention to abide by SFA’s
policies and procedures and to accept the responsibilities set forth in this manual. They shall
at all times discharge their duties with efficiency, diligence and fidelity and work honestly and
conscientiously for SFA.
2.4 Core Values and behaviours
The core values and behaviours define who we are and provide the footing for the Foundation
success. Upon approval by the Board and Management. These are:
• Act with Respect: SFA endeavors to serves its stakeholders and staff with passion
and courage, aiming to give all a chance to a decent life and contributing to the
betterment of humanity through the power of science and innovation.
• Embrace Diversity and ensure Inclusion: SFA values and welcomes a diversity of
staff and others, as an organisation that is enriched by many experiences and
perspectives, sharing of best practices and equal opportunity to everyone,
irrespective of race, age, gender, sexual orientation, status, colour, class, ethnicity,
disability, location and religion.
• Nurture Innovativeness: SFA encourages creativity, contemplative thinking,
flexibility and adaptability in our approaches to our work, in alignment with our
mission and to benefit our stakeholders.
• Ensure Accountability and Transparency: Ensure responsible practices and
adherence to sound ethical principles and compliance with standards and
regulations, and strives to minimise harm to human health and the environment by
supporting eco-friendly technologies and initiatives. Ensure decisions are made with
openness and honesty.
• Care: All staff members are encouraged to make the effort to understand every
individual and what matters to them. Recognise the value that each person
contributes and support others to grow and work in the ways that bring out their
best.
All individuals covered under this manual have obligations that directly relate to these
principles. The obligations contained in this policy define the standards of conduct required
by all individuals.
2.5 Standards of performance
All SFA employees will:
• Carry out official decisions and policies faithfully and impartially
• carry out official directions and policies in a faithful and impartial manner
• Create a SFAe work environment
• Adhere to professional codes of conduct where applicable
• Report fraudulent or corrupt conduct appropriately
• Take reasonable steps to protect confidential information
• Maintain their professional skills and keep up to date in their area of expertise
• Ensure they are informed of SFA policies and guidelines
2.6 Privacy and Confidentiality
SFA employees are not allowed to disclose or use any records, data or information, that are
accessed by them in the course of employment, except as required in the normal course of
such employment and as approved in advance by the Executive Director. Any such records,
files, and information shall remain the property of the SFA.
In accepting an appointment to SFA, staff members signify their intention to abide by all SFA’s
policies and procedures including the Data Protection Policy and to accept the responsibilities
set forth in this manual. They shall at all times discharge their duties with efficiency, diligence
and fidelity and work honestly and conscientiously for SFA.
Staff members shall exercise the utmost discretion concerning all matters of official business.
They shall not communicate to any person, verbally or in writing, any information known to
them due to their official position, which has not been made public, except in the proper
course of their duties or by authorisation of the Executive Director. Nor shall they, at any time,
use such information for private advantage. These obligations do not cease on termination of
the employment contract and shall continue for indefinite time.
All rights, including patents and copyrights in any work, invention and/or scientific discovery
developed by professional staff members while in the service of SFA are vested in SFA.
Unless specifically waived or transferred in writing by the Executive Director, all payments
and royalties emanating from the exercise of such rights are the property of SFA. Staff
members who believe that aspects of their work may be copyrighted or patented should
discuss this with the Executive Director.
SFA employees must respect the privacy of others and ensure that personal information
accessed is used only for SFA purposes and is not to be disclosed except where authorised
by legislation. Personal information in this case relates to all information that is not in the
public domain and has not been declared by the employee as information open to access by
all.
Employees who have access to such information have a duty to maintain the confidentiality,
integrity and security of such information, irrespective of the storage medium. Employees are
required to report to their supervisor or other appropriate person any actual or suspected
misuse of private information.
2.7 Conflict of interest
The Executive Director, Board Members and Management Members of SFA who feel that
their roles and responsibilities in other organisations may potentially be in conflict with those
of SFA must bring these to the attention of the Board.
All Employees of SFA should disclose to SFA any financial interest they may have in any
organisation from which the SFA proposes to obtain services or equipment or enter into any
contract that would result in a financial transaction.
Staff members (or office holders) who have occasion to deal in their official capacity with any
matter involving a business concern in which they hold a financial interest, shall disclose the
nature of that interest to the immediate supervisor. The mere holding of shares in a company
shall not constitute a financial interest within the meaning of this rule.
Staff members who feel that any of their outside interests may be potentially in conflict with
those of SFA should report these interests to their immediate Supervisor/Head of unit or
department. The Supervisor will then refer the information to Head of Human Resources. The
staff member will take the necessary action to avoid potential conflict and advise the HR
accordingly. Staff are expected to refer to the SFA conflict of interest policy which should be
adhered to.
2.8 Outside Employment
Full time employees of SFA must gain the prior approval of the Executive Director before they
engage in any consultancy or outside employment that is related in any way to their
employment at SFA.
Part time employees must inform the Executive Director of any other employment. This must
not conflict with SFA duties.
When an outside assignment is related to the work of SFA, and it is in SFA’s interest to have
the staff member undertake the assignment, the Executive Director will establish the
conditions under which the assignment may be accepted.
2.9 Honoraria, Gifts and Courtesies
SFA discourages the receipt of any gifts or benefits by employees in connection with their
employment or position except where this may arise in an official capacity. In such cases,
all such gifts or benefits should be disclosed. It is mandatory for employees who receive
money or gifts valued at USD 100 and above to declare this to Management who would
give direction on how the gift should be treated.
Staff members must seek authorization before accepting honoraria, cash awards, honours,
decorations, favours or gifts of significant value from any individual or organization related
to SFA. Failure to consult may result in disciplinary action.
2.10 Political and Other Voluntary Affiliations
Staff members are encouraged to exercise the right to vote but shall not engage in any
political activity, which is inconsistent with, or might negatively impact the independence or
impartiality that the Foundation stands for.
Any staff member who becomes a candidate for a public office of a political character shall
resign from the Africa Foundation for Science and Innovation.
The SFA employees may be members of political parties, professional or other interests or
charitable groups, and engagement with the wider community is encouraged provided that
the involvement does not conflict with their duties or violate any legal law.
2.11 Sexual harassment
Sexual harassment is an unlawful and prohibited conduct. Employees shall at all times, treat
other employees respectfully and with dignity, in a manner so as not to offend the sensibilities
of a co-worker. Management is committed to enforce its sexual harassment policy at all levels.
The Foundation considers the definition of sexual harassment as provided in the Kenyan
Constitution which postulates that an employee is sexually harassed if the employer of that
employee or a representative of that employer or a co-worker: -
a) Directly or indirectly requests that employee for sexual intercourse, sexual contact or any
other form of sexual activity that contains an implied or express―
• Promise of preferential treatment in employment;
• Threat of detrimental treatment in employment; or
• Threat about the present or future employment status of the employee;
b) Uses language whether written or spoken of a sexual nature;
c) Uses visual material of a sexual nature; or
d) Shows physical behaviour of a sexual nature which directly or indirectly subjects the
employee to behaviour that is unwelcome or offensive to that employee and that by its
nature has a detrimental effect on that employees employment, job performance, or job
satisfaction.
A complaint relating to sexual harassment should be lodged directly with Management. All
complaints of sexual harassment will be kept confidential and fully investigated. Only those,
who have an immediate need to know, will or may find out the identity of the complainant or
the alleged harasser. If deemed guilty of sexual harassment, the offender will be dismissed
in accordance with the SFA disciplinary procedures.
2.12 HIV and AIDS Policy
The SFA will not tolerate discrimination against employees or applicants living with or affected
by HIV or AIDS. SFA’s overall policy aims to encourage infected persons to feel free to report
any form of discrimination against them and recognises three guiding principles:
a) Employees need information and training regarding HIV and AIDS, how to prevent the
spread of HIV, how to protect themselves from the infection and its treatment.
b) The Foundation is committed to ensuring that employees with HIV and AIDS are not
discriminated against in any manner and that all personal information is kept strictly
confidential.
Accordingly, SFA has established the following guidelines to serve as the basis for handling
employee situations and concerns related to HIV infection and AIDS.
a) The SFA will treat HIV infection and AIDS the same as other illnesses in terms of all our
employee policies and benefits, including leave of absence. Employees living with, or
affected by, HIV infection and AIDS, will be treated with compassion and understanding.
b) The SFA does not require HIV testing for current employees or applicants. HIV status
will not influence decisions about hiring, termination, promotion, compensation,
annual reviews, or other aspects of employment.
c) Co-worker concerns will be handled in an educational fashion. Co-workers are
expected to continue working relationships with any employee who has HIV infection
or AIDS. Co-workers, who refuse to work with, withhold services from, harass, or
otherwise discriminate against an employee with HIV infection or AIDS will be subject
to the same disciplinary procedures that apply to other policy violations.
d) An employee's health condition is private and confidential. Under no circumstances will
an employee’s health status be revealed to a third party without the employee’s consent.
An employee with HIV or AIDS is under no obligation to disclose his or her condition to a
manager or any other employee of the SFA. Managers are expected to take careful
precautions to protect the confidentiality of information regarding any employee's health
condition, including an employee with AIDS or HIV infection.
e) Employees living with HIV or AIDS should feel free to confidentially discuss any issues
regarding this policy with their supervisor. Employees living with or affected by HIV or
AIDS, and those who have any related concerns, are encouraged to contact their
supervisors to discuss their concerns and obtain information.
2.13 Substance abuse
The Foundation’s desire is to provide a drug-free, healthful, and SFAe workplace. Employees
are required to report to work in a condition to perform their jobs in a SFAe, efficient, and
satisfactory manner.
The presence of alcohol and other drugs on the job and the influences of those substances
on employees during working hours are inconsistent with the objectives of a drug and alcohol
free workplace and will not be tolerated.
While in the workplace and while conducting business-related activities of SFA, no employee
may use, possess, manufacture, distribute, sell, or be under the influence of alcohol or illegal
drugs or use legal drugs illegally.
In addition, the legal use of prescribed drugs is permitted on the job only if it does not impair
an employee's ability to meet standards and perform the essential functions of the job in a
SFAe manner that does not endanger other individuals, equipment, or property in the
workplace.
The SFA also maintains a non-smoking policy regarding the use of tobacco within office
premises. As such, SFA is a no smoking zone.
Violations of this policy may lead to disciplinary action, up to and including termination of
employment.
2.14 Diversity-positive Recruitment
Before launching any recruitment, SFA examines whether the staffing need can be used to
meet its gender and diversity staffing strategies for furthering the career of existing staff.
When neither of these strategies is applicable, SFA proceeds to open competitive
recruitment. SFA’s primary consideration in recruiting staff is to secure the highest standards
of competence and commitment to its mission and values.
As an equal opportunity employer with a continental mandate, SFA believes that the diversity
of its staff contributes to organisational effectiveness and impact. To increase staff diversity,
SFA particularly encourages applications from women and other minorities. SFA recruits staff
impartially through open competition and through processes that neither discriminate against
nor unduly favour candidates on the basis of gender, race, national or social origin, religion,
political affiliation, age, family size, marital status or any other form of personal identity; nor
on physical disability not relevant to the assignment.
SFA applies consistent and fair recruitment and appointment practices to ensure that existing
staff as well as external candidates have equal opportunity for job openings. All vacant
positions are public to staff at the start of the recruitment process. Recruitment at SFA is
based on the principle of open competition and selection on merit, the basic elements of
which include:
a) Broad publicity – vacancies are publicised in a way that spreads the recruitment net
widely and optimises potential candidates’ opportunity to apply.
b) Focus on minority groups – special efforts are made to encourage applications from
groups that might otherwise be under-represented during the recruitment process.
c) Focus on merit – ranking on the basis of the highest standards of competence – the
knowledge, skills and personal qualities required to carry out SFA’s objectives,
together with commitment to SFA’s mission and values.
d) Enhancing diversity – where selection occurs between candidates of similar
competence and commitment, the decision would generally favour the candidate who
most enhances SFA’s diversity.
3. EMPLOYMENT PRACTICE
3.1 Definition of Employment Contracts
Persons may be employed by SFA under the following classifications:
a) Full term (on contract)
A full term employee is one who is hired to fill a full-time position in SFA for an agreed
upon duration of time. Such an employee is paid by the regular payroll procedures,
and enjoys all of the benefits as defined by SFA for such employees. A full term
employee may also be hired in special circumstances on a part-time basis and is
required to work.
i. Reduced hours per week/month; or
ii. Reduced days per week/month or;
iii. A combination of reduced hours and days per week or month.
b) Short term/Temporary employee
A short term or temporary employee is one who is hired:
i. To fill a position full-time in SFA on a temporary basis;
ii. As a replacement for a full term employee on approved leave of absence;
iii. In a temporary office
Short-term appointments for specialized ‘professional services’ employment at SFA can be
approved in situations where regular qualified staff are not available. These appointments are
on a limited-term contract, initially for a period of one year and are subject to a further one
year extension at the end of which there must be a definite separation. Such employment is
governed by different sets of policies. SFA may also engage a short term employee on a
part-time basis and pay them at a pro-rated fee for that position.
c) Consultants
A Consultant is an individual or firm that is engaged by SFA for a defined purpose with
specified deliverables that are set out in a Terms of Reference (TOR), and for a fixed
duration of time. Such employment is subject to special terms and conditions agreed
to by both parties, namely the individual and SFA.
Consultants working for SFA may be hired within the approved budgets but the total
costs for any one consultancy agreement, including fees, travel and subsistence, may
not exceed the limits as established for that specific consultancy.
The conditions for employment accorded to full term or temporary employees shall not
apply to consultants.
3.2 Position Description
3.2.1 Classification levels for new positions
SFA endeavours to ensure classifications of positions reflect comparable job worth and
market value by frequently conducting job evaluations to determine appropriate position
classifications. When undertaking a job evaluation exercise, a questionnaire regarding the
employees job description will be provided to staff for completion in order to obtain various
details about the duties and responsibilities of a new or amended vacant general employee
position which requires evaluation. This document will be considered as the basis for both
the evaluation of the position and the development of the position description.
Alternatively, a position description may be developed directly by the employing department
or section and forwarded to the Head of Human Resources in order that a job evaluation may
be undertaken. Management will approve the classification in consultation with the respective
head of department.
3.2.2 Reclassification of existing positions
A fixed term full or part time employee who is appointed to a position of greater than 12
months duration may apply for a review of the classification level of their position. The
employee is required to have occupied the position for a period of 12 months or more. Unless
otherwise determined by SFA Management, applications for reclassification may be initiated
on an ‘as needs’ basis by:
• The authorised head of department of section, having reviewed the duties and
responsibilities of the position; or the incumbent of a position.
A written application for reclassification should be submitted to the SFA Management who
will investigate this need. Management will respond to the applicant in 30 working days of a
decision to either accept, defer, or refuse the application. Grounds for refusal or deferral of
an application may relate to operational considerations including:
• A position will not normally be reviewed twice within a 12 month period;
• The application shows that when compared with previous documentation the duties
and responsibilities of the position have not changed significantly since it was last
evaluated; or
• The position is part of a proposed reorganisation or job redesign exercise to be
completed within six (6) months.
Where a decision is made to accept the application, the application should be evaluated within
four (4) weeks of the last day of the quarter in which it was lodged with the Human Resources.
SFA will engage an expert to assist with the job evaluation exercise. The expert will meet with
the incumbent and nominated supervisor(s) as part of the review process to obtain and clarify
further information about the position and perform an evaluation of the position. For purposes
of ensuring the integrity of the process, two or more evaluators may be selected to conduct
the process. Upon completion of the evaluation process, evaluators will be required to submit
a report on the outcomes and recommendations to the Head of Human Resources.
SFA Management will then consider the recommendations considering organisational and
operational matters and determine appropriate action for each position. The respective
departments and job incumbents will be notified in writing of the outcome of each application
for reclassification. This will be followed by the initiation of any required action in the areas of
establishment, redeployment or recruitment.
3.2.3 Positions reclassified upwards
Where the position is reclassified upward by one classification level, the employee will be
paid at step one of the new classification, unless recommended otherwise by the Executive
Director in consultation with the Head of Department or section and the Head of Human
Resources.
3.2.4 Positions reclassified downwards
Where a position is reclassified downwards, the employee will undertake the duties of
the position while continuing to be remunerated at their existing salary level. The Head
of Human Resources in consultation with the head of section or department will initiate
job redesign.
3.2.5 Feedback
Applicants are encouraged to request feedback concerning the Reclassification
process and outcome by contacting the Head of Human Resources upon receipt of the
outcome.
3.3 Recruitment, Appointment, Transfers and Renewals/Extensions
So far as practicable, the SFA as an equal opportunities employer, will endeavour to hire the
most qualified applicant based on educational background, previous experience, proven
skills, desirable character traits, and growth potential. The character traits required may be
defined by the selection committee if need be depending on the kind of position.
Appointments shall be made on competitive basis; due regard being made to the mandate
and operational efficiency and effectiveness of SFA
The objective of recruitment is to identify a pool of qualified candidates to select from for each
new position. Any vacant post will be announced internally to SFA staff. If no SFA staff is
qualified, then the post will be advertised externally using appropriate local and international
channels. Internal promotion is also encouraged but the process must be competitive.
3.3.1 General
SFA’s objective in the appointment, transfer or promotion of staff members is to secure,
through open competition, the highest standards of competence, efficiency and integrity
available. In addition, SFA is committed to maintaining the diversity of its staff in terms of both
gender and nationality. SFA believes that such diversity contributes to effectiveness and
organizational excellence and impact.
When recruiting, SFA will pay particular attention to gender balance and applicants from
diverse ethnic and national balance in backgrounds pursuit of the objective to select the
individual backgrounds. The objective is to select the individual determined to be the best
person for the position.
SFA will apply consistent and fair recruitment and appointment practices to ensure that
current staff members, as well as external candidates, have equal opportunity for job
openings. All vacant positions will be made known to current staff members at the start of the
recruitment process.
3.3.2 Recruitment Principles
Recruitment and appointment at SFA are based on the principle of open competition on merit,
the basic elements of which are:
a. adequate publicity - vacancies are publicised to provide potential candidates with
every reasonable opportunity to apply;
b. special efforts are made to encourage applications from groups that might otherwise
be under-represented in the candidate list;
c. absence of discrimination - selections are made impartially under processes that will
neither discriminate nor unduly favour candidates on the basis of gender, race,
national or social origin, religion, political affiliation, or any other form of personal
identity; age, marital status, or family size; physical disability not relevant to the
assignment; and
d. ranking on the basis of the highest standards of efficiency, competence, effectiveness,
integrity, professional qualifications, and appropriate experience to carry out SFA's
objectives.
SFA will not appointment family relationship of current staff member (e.g. husband, wife,
partner, father, mother, son, daughter, brother or sister).
3.3.3 Establishment of new positions
When the need to establish a new position has been determined, the department head should
discuss with Management concerning the classification and salary group of the new position.
The requesting department will provide a job description for the position.
The same procedure will be used for recruitment of new staff or reclassification of existing
posts. Such descriptions shall also be used for vacancy notices and other personnel
operations, as appropriate. Staff members may request reconsideration of the classification
of their post.
3.3.4 Job Descriptions
Job descriptions are job specifications and as such are illustrative and not restrictive, which
means that the typical duties set forth in the job description are not intended to exclude other
duties and responsibilities of a similar kind which are not mentioned. Job descriptions are
specific to each position and establish essential functions and responsibilities of each
position.
A description shall be prepared for each position and will comprise the title, roles and
responsibilities, reporting structure, and the relevant qualifications and experience of the job
incumbent.
3.3.5 Announcement of Vacancies
Vacancies for posts shall be advertised internally to the staff except where:
a. No staff member is fully qualified for the post, in which case the senior management
team shall determine whether the post shall be filled by external advertisement or
secondment from a roaster of eligible candidates or from any other source.
b. The post is upgraded, as the result of gradual assumption of higher-level duties and
responsibilities, by the incumbent, who is considered to have the requisite
qualifications and is recommended for upgrading by the Department Head.
c. In the judgment of the Executive Director, a placement problem could be solved by
the transfer of a staff member into the vacant post.
d. A staff member is transferred to a technically analogous post of the same grade for
which, in the judgement of the Executive Director, the staff member is qualified.
When a vacancy is advertised, a vacancy announcement is prepared based on the post
description. It shall include the title, grade and the location of the post, the length of
assignment and the expected level of skill and competence. The announcement will also
indicate whether the vacancy is internal or also open to external candidates. Written
applications will be required for a position.
Recruitment for senior positions will require open advertising in order to make information
about the positions available to all potentially qualified candidates. However, first
consideration shall be given to the possibility of promoting qualified staff members, who have
successfully completed their probationary period.
The position of Executive Director is advertised widely through the local paper(s) and
advertised through appropriate channels internationally.
3.3.6 Employee selection
Selection of candidates is based on merit and the principles of equal opportunities for all will
apply. There shall be no discrimination based on race, colour, age, religion, sex, nationality,
origin, ancestry, marital status, HIV and AIDS status, disability, political belief, or any other
status protected by law, in the selection, appointment, and compensation of staff members.
Under the authority conferred upon him/her by the Management, the power of appointment
of staff members is vested in the Executive Director. Interviews of prospective employees
will involve the Head of Human Resources and the department head in whose section the
position lies vacant.
Staff members may be designated to participate in the screening of applications and
interviews as appropriate for the position being recruited. Applications will be reviewed and
candidates short-listed for interview.
Interviews may be conducted by a team of two people or a panel depending on the seniority
of the position. A representative of the recruiting department should be present at the final
interviews if not through the entire process.
There will be a record kept of reasons for acceptance and rejection, signed by the interviewer.
The paramount consideration in the appointment, transfer, or promotion of staff members,
shall be the necessity for securing the highest standards of competence. Without prejudice
to the recruitment of fresh talent at all levels, the fullest regard shall be in filling vacancies, to
the requisite qualifications and experience of persons already in the service of SFA.
Staff members in the professional categories shall be recruited on a local or international
basis. Support staff shall be recruited from within commuting distance of the duty station,
except when it is not possible to secure qualified persons within commuting distance.
For the position of Executive Director, the Committee set up by the Board will be responsible
for recruitment. This committee will shortlist three applicants, which may be invited for
interview by the Committee and subsequent recommendation for appointment.
3.3.7 Documentation
All recruitment and selection documentation must be returned to the Head of Human
Resources for record keeping and confidentially secured. Comments made by interview panel
members on potential candidates for selection will remain on the vacancy file for the position
for which interviews were conducted.
3.4 Appointment and Acceptance of Offer
On final selection and approval of the chosen candidate, the human resources will make an
offer of appointment to the preferred candidate.
Offers and Contract of appointment, indicating the base salary for the position, will be made
in writing and signed by the Executive Director. A copy of this manual and any relevant
Personnel Policy will be included with such letters, and shall be considered an integral part
of the employment contract.
Offers of base salary are normally made at the entry point of the appropriate grade. However,
in exceptional circumstances, SFA may consider offering a higher base salary.
An appointment becomes effective only after the offer is accepted in writing by the appointee.
Until SFA receives the signed acceptance letter, it may rescind the offer by written notification
from the Executive Director. The preferred candidate will be required to provide an
acceptance in writing within the period specified in the letter of offer. Where the preferred
candidate declines the offer, an offer of appointment can be made without re-advertisement
to the candidate who received the second highest ratings against the selection criteria as
indicated in the selection documentation.
Where the appointee ceases employment at SFA within three months of the closing date of
the original vacancy advertisement, an offer may be made without re-advertisement to the
candidate who received the second highest ratings against the selection criteria as indicated
in the selection documentation. This can occur only where the position description has not
changed.
Where an identical position to that advertised becomes vacant within three months of the
closing date of the original vacancy advertisement, an offer may be made without readvertisement to the candidate who received the second highest ratings against the selection
criteria as indicated in the selection documentation.
Appointment will be considered official only when SFA and the employee have signed an
employment contract. SFA is not responsible for the loss of other employment (e.g.,
resignation from prior position, or forfeiting other job offers) prior to the signing of a contract.
If any information in the application is found to be false after appointment, SFA reserves the
right to take disciplinary action which may include termination of employment.
3.4.1 Contracts of employment
Upon appointment, each staff member shall receive a contract of employment in accordance
with these regulations which is signed by the Executive Director or his/her delegated
representative.
The contract of employment contains, expressly or by reference, all the terms and conditions
of employment. All entitlements of staff members are therefore strictly limited to those
contained, expressly or by reference, in their letters of employment. The letter offering
appointment, the terms of employment and the attached HR Policy and Procedures Manual
constitute the contract of employment.
The letter offering appointment shall state:
• That the appointment is subject to the provisions of SFA Personnel Policy and
Procedures Manual applicable to the category of appointment in question and to
changes which may be duly made in such regulations and rules from time to time;
• The nature of the appointment and the duty station;
• The date at which the staff member is required to start his or her duties;
• The contractual period, its expiration date, the notice required to terminate it and the
period of probation, if any;
• The category, grade level, commencing rate of salary and if increments are allowable,
the scale of increments and the maximum attainable.
• The probation Period
• Any specific condition related to the offer
For all staff, a copy of this HR Policy Manual accompanies all appointment offers. Candidates
will indicate their acceptance by signing and returning a copy of the terms of employment. In
accepting appointment, it will be presumed that staff members accept the conditions laid
down in this Manual.
The term of appointment of the Executive Director will be three years, renewable, with a
probationary period of six months. Renewal of appointment of the Executive Director shall be
subject to extensive review of performance. Review shall be initiated six months prior to end
of contract and shall be concluded with a recommendation to renew or otherwise at least
three months before end of contract.
3.4.2 An additional fixed term contract
Under exceptional circumstances where the need arises for an employee on fixed term
contract to be extended or renewed, the incumbent’s performance will be reviewed through
a thorough comprehensive performance review process. If found satisfactory, the Executive
Director in consultation with the Head of Human Resources can approve extension of the
contract.
3.4.3 Effective date
The appointment of staff members who, at the time of initial appointment, are not residing
within commuting distance of the duty station, shall take effect from the day on which they
begin travel to assume their posts.
The appointment of staff members, who at the time of their initial appointment, reside within
commuting distance of the duty station, shall take effect upon the date on which they assume
their posts.
3.4.4 Staff Orientation
Each new member of staff is required to undergo orientation, the purpose of which is to
introduce him/her to the people he/she will be working with and to familiarize him/ her with
SFA policies and procedures and with his/her job description. The Head of Human Resources
in collaboration with the new employee’s supervisor is responsible for employee orientation.
Staff members are encouraged to familiarize themselves with this manual and any issues
they may have can then be raised during orientation.
3.4.5 Probation Period
The probationary period for the Foundation staff is six months. In this period, the employee
will be provided with an orientation to the work and operations of SFA. During the probation
period, the employee is eligible for all benefits and entitlements, which are pro-rated to the
starting date of employment for employees joining SFA during the year.
The purpose of the probation period is to give all newly appointed staff member’s adequate
time and working conditions to demonstrate their suitability. This is judged by their ability to:
• Meet the requirements of the position to which they have been appointed,
• Perform according to SFA’s standards, and
• Demonstrate behaviour consistent with their obligations as an SFA staff member.
During the probation period, the appointee will receive regular performance appraisals and
feedback. The employee’s supervisor will assess the quality of the individual's work and
determine if they are suitable for continued employment with SFA. If the Supervisor is not
satisfied with the performance of the staff member by the end of the probation period, the
appointment may be terminated by one month’s notice in writing.
Upon completion of the probation period, any of the following outcomes could result:
a) Confirmation of employment. The new employee will receive notice from his/her
supervisor that the probation period has been completed successfully.
b) Extension of probation. If the employee has not satisfactorily met their employment
requirements, probation may be extended by an additional six months.
Termination of employment with SFA. In the event that an employee is determined
unsuitable for continued employment, the employee will be released. Should the
employee equally feel that their affiliation with SFA is not working, they can equally
terminate their employment with SFA. In both cases, a notice period of one month or
three months for administrative staff and professional staff respectively is required.
3.4.6 Confirmation of Appointment
Confirmation of appointment of staff members is dependent upon satisfactory completion of
his or her probationary period, entailing satisfactory performance of his or her duties and
responsibilities and satisfactory conduct as evaluated by his or her supervisor and
Department Head.
When it is considered that further time is required to determine a staff member’s suitability,
or that the probationary period has not been satisfactorily completed, the Executive Director
may authorize either extension of the probationary period for a further period up to 6 months,
or separation or termination of the staff member, in accordance with the applicable provisions
of this Manual.
The Human Resources office will keep track of all the contracts and advice the management
on the way forward, i.e. if a member of staff is to be confirmed through a formal written
notification of confirmation.
3.4.7 Acting Appointments
Whenever a vacancy (temporary or permanent) occurs, an acting appointment may be made
to the position in order to ensure continuity of operations. Selection for acting appointments
shall be based upon the candidate satisfying prescribed requirements of the position. In the
event of equality of efficiency and competence of two or more employees, consideration shall
be given to the experience and ability to delivery on the acting position of the employees
available for such acting appointments
• When an opportunity for an acting appointment occurs, it will be the primary
responsibility of the relevant Departmental Head to identify the most suitable
candidate from either within the particular Department or from another, if appropriate.
At any stage, advice may be sought from Management on the identification of the
most suitable candidate.
• The Executive Director or duly authorized representative must approve all acting
appointments.
• An acting appointment, unless specifically stated, shall give the employee no special
claim for promotion to the position.
• For purposes of performance evaluation, an employee acting in a higher position shall
be treated as though he/she were promoted to the position.
• Where an employee is appointed to act in a higher or same position than his/her
substantive position and acts for a period of more than 4 consecutive weeks, he/she
shall be eligible, to earn an acting allowance equivalent 10% of current base salary for
the acting position however the their monthly pay should not exceed the base salary
of the acting position. The benefits payable to a staff member in an acting position will
remain unchanged.
3.4.8 Information to be supplied by Staff Members
Staff members shall be responsible, on appointment, for supplying whatever information may
be required for determining their status under this Manual or for completing administrative
arrangements in connection with their appointments.
Specifically, this requirement shall include information on nationality, marital status,
dependency status and information relevant to the designation of a beneficiary. Employees
shall also be responsible for promptly notifying the Human Resources, in writing, of any
subsequent changes affecting their status.
A staff member who is arrested and charged with an offence, other than minor traffic violation,
and summoned before a court of law, as a defendant in a criminal proceeding, or convicted
or imprisoned for an offence other than a minor traffic violation, shall immediately report the
fact to the management.
Staff members may, at any time, be required by SFA to supply information concerning the
facts prior to their appointment and relevant to their suitability, or concerning facts relevant to
their integrity, conduct and service as a staff member. SFA also reserves the right to request
for a certificate of good conduct from any member of staff.
3.4.9 Nationality
In the application of this Manual, the Foundation shall not recognize more than one nationality
for each staff member.
When a staff member has been legally accorded nationality status by more than one state,
the staff member’s nationality for the purpose of this Manual, shall be the nationality of the
state with which the staff member is, in the opinion of the HR, most closely associated, due
regard being taken of the staff member’s presentation.
Staff members, who intend to acquire a permanent residence status in any country other than
that of their nationality, or other than that of their country of permanent residence, as
established for administrative purposes, shall notify the Head of Human Resources of this
intention before the change in residence status or nationality becomes final.
3.4.10 Re-Employment
A former staff member, who is re-employed, shall be given a new appointment. If reemployment takes place within 12 months of separation from service, the re-employment can,
at the option of SFA, be considered as reinstatement. In the event of a new appointment
being granted, its terms shall be duly applicable without regard to any former period of
service.
3.4.11 Loan and Secondment
Under this Manual, a loan or secondment is defined as the movement of a staff member from
one organization to another, for a limited period, during which period the staff member will be
subject to the administrative supervision of the receiving organization but will continue to be
subject to the policies contained in this Manual.
The Executive Director may loan or second the service of an SFA staff member to another
international agency or to an inter-governmental organization. Such loan or secondment in
no way diminishes the rights or entitlements of a staff member under his/her letter of
appointment to SFA.
When an individual is released on loan or secondment for service with SFA, for example, by
an international organization, university, private firm, or similar body, the Executive Director
shall make individual agreements under which the services of the individual shall be obtained,
utilised, and remunerated. These agreements will take into account the individual’s service
rights, including return rights, and the individual’s pension and comparable entitlements.
3.7 Retirement Age
All the Foundation staff will retire at the age of 65 years. Continuation and/or employment of
professional staff above this age will require the approval of the Board.
3.8 Separation from Service
Separation is the action by which a staff member ceases to be employed by SFA. Separation
takes place upon termination, resignation, retirement, expiration of appointment, death,
Redundancy or transfer to other organizations.
3.8.1 Involuntary Termination
Termination, within the meaning of this Manual, is a separation initiated by SFA. It does not
include retirement. The Executive Director may terminate the contract of employment of a
staff member for reasons relating but not limited to:
• The services of the individual concerned prove unsatisfactory;
• The individual acts in contravention of the obligations stated in these regulations;
• Reasons of health incapacitation;
• Such other reasons as maybe specified in the letter of Termination.
The Human Resources may terminate the contract of employment of a staff member for
reasons other than those stated above, provided that the action would be in the best interests
of SFA. If the necessities of service require that the appointments of staff members be
terminated as a result of abolition of posts or reduction of staff, preference shall be given to
the retention of staff with the best record of satisfactory service, subject to the availability of
suitable posts, in which their services can be effectively utilized.
A staff member whose appointment is to be terminated, shall be given not less than 30 days
written notice of such termination, or such notice as may otherwise be stipulated in the letter
of appointment thereof. Payment, where applicable, of termination indemnity, shall be made
by SFA in accordance with the rates specified in the terms of service. In lieu of notice, the
Human Resources may authorize compensation calculated based on the salary and
allowances, which the staff member would have received, had the date of termination been
at the end of the notice period. Termination emoluments, including accumulation of annual
leave are calculated as if employment had continued until the end of the notice period. No
notice is required for summary dismissal.
In the case of the Directors, appointment may be terminated, by giving not less than 90 days
written notice of such termination or such notice as may otherwise be stipulated in the letter
of appointment thereof. Payment, where applicable, of termination indemnity, shall be made
by SFA in accordance with the rates specified in the terms of service. In lieu of notice, the
Management may authorize compensation calculated based on the salary and allowances,
which the staff member would have received, had the date of termination been at the end of
the notice period. Termination emoluments, including accumulation of annual leave are
calculated as if employment had continued until the end of the notice period.
3.8.2 Redundancy
If SFA must terminate an appointment prematurely because the position is abolished, the
staff member receives all payments and benefits. The staff member receives a minimum of 3
months’ notice, payment for unused annual leave in accordance with SFA’s policy on leave
accrual, and 15 days’ pay for every year worked as provided for in Kenya’s Employment Act.
He/she is also entitled to his/her Pension Fund earnings that are allowed by current legislation
but these are processed and settled directly with the departing employee by the Administrator
of the Fund as is required by law.
3.8.3 Termination for Health Reasons
An employee’s contract of the employment may be terminated if staff member has not
attained the mandatory age of retirement, if he/she considers that the staff member is unable
to perform the duties assigned to him/her because of physical or mental limitations. If,
although the staff member would have been suitable for another post in SFA commensurate
with his/her qualifications, no such post is vacant. The appointment of a staff member in this
case will only be terminated after exhaustion of sick leave entitlements.
Before a final decision to terminate the appointment of a staff member is taken, the staff
member must be given a formal letter or confidential memorandum, on the action proposed
and the reasons thereof. Within 15 working days of receipt of this memorandum, the staff
member will respond in writing, either accepting termination or otherwise request the
formation of a Medical Board to advise on the medico-legal aspects of the case.
The Medical Board will comprise of a medical representative of the staff member, one medical
practitioner selected by the SFA, and another medical practitioner selected by the two
practitioners aforesaid, and a legal representative to continuously provide guidance on the
legal aspects of the case. The Medical Board will submit its report and recommendations to
the Executive Director for decision.
If the right to convene a Medical Board is exercised, any appeal filed in accordance with this
Manual shall be restricted to the legal and procedural aspects of the case, to the exclusion of
the medical aspects on which the
Executive Director’s decision shall be deemed final.
3.8.4 Abandonment of Post
An employee is deemed to have abandoned his/her job when for a period of five (5)
consecutive days the employee has been absent without approval. This employee is
subject to termination. Supervisors should implement the following procedure upon
approval of the Executive Director:
Documentation should be provided to the Head of Human Resources reflecting
• The length of the unapproved leave and any known circumstances
• Efforts expended to contact the employee
The Head of Human Resources shall send a certified letter to the last known address of the
employee informing him/her of the imminent loss of employment and giving the employee a
timeframe in which to respond.
If the employee fails to respond within 15 days, or responds with a reason that is
unacceptable to the supervisor, the Department Manager, with the approval of the Head
of Human Resources may terminate appointment of the employee.
To do so:
• A certified letter must be sent to the employee notifying him/her of the
termination and referring him/her to the Office of Head of Human Resources for
exit interview.
• All passwords and information systems accounts must be deactivated by the
supervisor.
Letter of termination must be prepared and handed over to the employee. The date of
termination shall be the first day after the close of the third day of unauthorized absence.
3. 9 Resignation
A resignation, within the meaning of this Manual, is a separation initiated by a staff member.
Staff members may resign from SFA upon giving the Executive Director the notice required
under the terms and conditions of employment.
The Directors and Managers shall give a 3 months written notice. All other staff shall give one
month’s written notice of resignation. The Executive Director may accept resignation on
shorter notice, or waive this requirement.
If a resignation is submitted without such notice, a deduction is made from accumulated
annual leave to cover the remainder of the notice period.
3.10 Expiration of Appointment
An appointment expires automatically, and without prior notice on the expiration date
specified in the letter of appointment. However, staff members will normally be advised, as
far in advance as possible, before their appointment is due to expire, whether or not their
appointment is to be extended or otherwise.
3.11 Death of an Employee
On receipt of advice that an employee has died Head of Human Resources will:
• Convey condolences in writing to the immediate family;
• Calculate outstanding salary and leave entitlements and as from the last known
working day as well as any accrued benefits, and action for payment;
• Advice the relevant Contribution Fund that the deceased may have been a part of, the
member’s details (date of death, name and address of next of kin, and name and
address of person handling estate).
3.12 Return of SFA Property
Any employee who is leaving the employ of the SFA is required to return all property in good
condition. Property belonging to the SFA may include, but is not limited to: equipment,
literature, staff cards, mobile phones, files, access keys, laptops and other computer
hardware and software.
It is the responsibility of the manager/supervisor of any employee who is leaving the SFA
to ensure that the Foundation’s property is returned prior to the cessation date.
3.13 Personnel Files and Records
Personnel files are confidential and should be kept in a locked filing cabinet under the
jurisdiction of the Head of Human Resources. Employees have the right to inspect and copy
the information contained in their own personnel files.
3.14 Exit Interview
All terminating employees are to meet with their supervisors on the last day of employment
to discuss details of the termination process and reason for termination. Terminating
employees will be required to complete an exit and clearance form. At that time, the employee
shall return all company property using the clearance form. The employee will then notify the
Finance Office about the disposition of final pay cheque and benefits, if any.
3.15 Consultancy and Other Non-SFA Paid Work
SFA will allow provision for staff to accept external consultancy studies or work relevant to
their duties at SFA. These external consultancies provide the staff with additional skills and
international exposure, which SFA can benefit from. Staff members should not allow these
other activities to interfere with the basic responsibilities of their posts.
There are three central principles limiting outside work:
• It must not impair the quality of the employee’s work
• It must not bring SFA into disrepute
• It must not put SFA at financial risk
Employees will not take assignments that are likely to take more than 10 days in any one
month. Permission for such assignments may be withheld if:
• The activity or activities in question will impair performance of the employee’s basic
responsibilities, for example because of unrealistic time commitment or because of
absences from the duty station;
• An unacceptable conflict of interest will result, for example, between the employee’s
responsibilities to SFA and his or her interest in the other organisation;
• There will be difficulties with donors, for example, as a result of an exclusivity clause;
• The activity is likely to bring SFA into disrepute.
The member of staff should submit to the scrutiny of the Executive Director or his/her
designated representative, any contract between him/her and an outside person or body,
subject to any relevant legal considerations.
If the employee is dissatisfied with refusal of permission, or with any conditions imposed on
him/her, he or she may appeal following the stated appeal procedure. The staff member
should be careful that he or she does not inappropriately hold himself/herself out as agent or
representative of SFA, nor as doing the work in the course of his or her employment with
SFA.
SFA should be fully compensated for the use of its staff or facilities. As such, subject to
variation and depending upon the circumstances of each individual case, the apportionment
of the net income deriving from such commercial exploitation will be 60 percent to SFA and
40 percent to the staff member.
As a guideline, SFA staff will charge a predetermined daily rates when on external
assignment.
These rates are indicative and are per day worked at the duty station. Half rates will be
charged for travel time.
4. PERFORMANCE MANAGEMENT AND STAFF EVALUATION
4.1 Staff Evaluation
Performance reviews are best viewed as a constructive, forward-looking process. All staff will
have an annual work performance review which will also provide the basis for developing a
staff development plan for the employee.
These reviews provide an opportunity to systematically review and discuss the performance
of staff over the review period, reflect on accomplishments, and identify priorities for staff
development and targets for improvements for the next period. This is also an opportunity for
the employee to receive feedback on their performance, and raise any concerns or issues
he/she may have that are integral to improved performance.
With the above understanding, SFA observes that performance s are not directly linked to
salary reviews. Salary reviews will be conducted at an entirely different time and their sole
focus is employee salary and benefits in view of the job and other environmental factors.
Employees are therefore encouraged to focus on the numerous benefits of the appraisal
relating to improved performance and personal and organisational development.
4.2 Process for Performance Reviews
The staff evaluation will take place every December and at the end of each probation period.
The review will be conducted by the employee's supervisor and will be confidential between
the employee, the supervisor and a HR Representative. The Chairman of the Board will be
responsible for the appraisal of the Executive Director
During the annual review phase the staff member and supervisor should meet to discuss how
well the staff member has met their work plan objectives. The focus of the annual review
meeting should be to:
• Recognise achievements
• Confirm what has already been discussed to date
• Discuss what will be documented in the Performance and Development Review
sections of the work plan
• Discuss any outstanding problems
• Review development activities undertaken
• Consider the work plan and development priorities for the next year
During the appraisal, the supervisor will ensure a conducive environment for discussions that
is free of any interruptions.
Quarterly reviews are highly recommended to ensure that remedial action is taken on an ongoing basis. Such reviews minimise surprises for either the staff member or supervisor during
the annual reviews.
The outcomes of the Annual Performance and Development Review discussion are recorded
in the appropriate sections of the work plan and should include:
• Comments about how the agreed objectives were met;
• Comments about development and support activities undertaken;
• An overall comment and rating on performance in relation to the agreed objectives set
out in the work plan;
• Space for supervisors to make recommendations about incremental progression.
At the end of the appraisal period both the supervisor and staff member sign the work plan
to confirm agreement of issues discussed. The supervisor retains the work plan and
provides a copy of the same to the staff member. The supervisor should additionally submit
a copy of the fully completed work plan and review document to Head of Finance and
Grants Management for staff records.
In situations where both the appraiser and appraisee fail to agree on current performance
levels or future targets, the matter shall be referred to the to the immediate higher
supervisor A third party may be involved to review the case for purposes of objectivity.
Performance contracts and targets will be prepared by the staff and his/her supervisor to
ensure that they are realistic and achievable within the stipulated time.
4.3 Rewarding Performance
Feedback to an employee on their performance in a timely manner will either reinforce
outstanding behaviours, or clarify specifically for the employee that their performance is not
acceptable and needs improvement. All performance, whether outstanding, acceptable, or
unacceptable should be acknowledged and recognized periodically during the performance
cycle. However, for performance extremes (exemplary or substandard displays of
performance) an employee should receive formal, written recognition immediately.
Supervisors are encouraged to distinguish and document incidents of exemplary
performance during the rating cycle. It is important to differentiate between performance that
is expected of the employee and performance that far exceeds expectations. It is important
to note that the receipt of an acknowledgment of outstanding performance does not guarantee
or necessarily warrant an overall rating of outstanding employee at the annual appraisal.
Employees who demonstrate outstanding behaviour will be rewarded through a variety of
mechanisms considered appropriate by management. These include and are not limited to
Certificates, Incentives, Capacity development and Promotions.
Similarly, supervisors should immediately identify poor, substandard or unacceptable
performance. Employees who fail to meet the required standards of performance will undergo
a performance improvement plan through coaching and counselling aimed at performance
improvement, leading up to, suspensions and termination if no change is realised.
4.4 Managing Performance for Improvement
The SFA is committed to excellence in performance and the success of its employees by
focusing on continuous improvement. SFA will thus provide a mechanism through
performance planning and review and employee supervision to support employees whose
performance is assessed as requiring improvement.
4.5 Staff Learning , Training and Development
SFA seeks to support the professional development of staff in areas considered relevant to
the employee's roles and responsibilities within the organisation. Discussions from the
performance appraisal will help to identify staff training and development needs. However,
employees are encouraged to continuously invest in different forms of training (short-term
training, seminars, workshops, evening classes, online courses) for self-development, which
further impacts on their performance.(Refer to Learning, Training and Development
Policy)
4.6 Initial counselling
Where a supervisor is of the view that the performance of an employee is unsatisfactory, the
supervisor will first counsel the employee on the nature of the improvement required and
develop and implement strategies to address underperformance. These strategies will be
given two months for all staff, having regard to the performance issues to be addressed.
A record of the counsel given will be kept and a copy supplied to the employee.
At this time, and if the supervisor believes it appropriate, the supervisor will direct the
employee to undertake a course of professional development or other appropriate
programmes designed to assist in improving performance.
4.6.1 Written advice of unsatisfactory performance
Where a supervisor believes that counselling has not produced the desired improvements
in performance, the supervisor will advise the employee, in writing, of the following:
• The specific areas of performance that are considered unsatisfactory,
• The nature of the improvement required over the next two months for all staff,
having regard to the performance issues to be addressed,
• The date proposed for a review of the specific areas of performance, and
• The availability of professional development and other resources to assist the
employee in improving. A copy will be provided to the Executive director and the
Head of Finance and Grants Management.
The employee will be required to respond to the supervisor within 10 working days from
the receipt of the supervisor’s written. The supervisor must give due and proper weight
to any response provided by the employee and will do one of the following:
• Confirm the advice of unsatisfactory performance and the remedial action required or
• Modify any or all of the particulars contained in the previous advice; or
• Withdraw the advice and ensure that no records relating to the advice are kept on the
employee’s file.
4.6.2 Review of progress
The supervisor will review whether or not the required improvement in the employee’s
performance has been made. This review will occur no earlier than the date set in the
written advice.
Where the supervisor is satisfied that the required improvements have been made, the
employee will be advised in writing and no further action taken.
4.6.3 Formal report
Where the supervisor believes that the performance of the employee continues to be
unsatisfactory, the supervisor, in consultation the Head of Human Resources, will make a
formal report to the Executive director clearly stating the aspects of performance seen as
unsatisfactory, the record of attempts to remedy the problem, and the recommended
disciplinary action.
The supervisor will provide the employee with a copy of the report at the time it is submitted
to the Executive director. The employee will be entitled to 10 working days from the receipt
of the supervisor’s report, to submit a written response to the Executive Director. Where the
report recommends disciplinary action, the employee may request that the matter be
reviewed by a third party for objectivity. (See appeal process in Section 8).
5 COMPENSATION POLICY AND PROCEDURES
5.1 Salaries and Related Allowances
Salary scales of Foundation staff will be determined by the Management with particular
reference to conditions offered by comparable international agencies and with due
consideration of the laws of the host country and the available budget to support such
payment.
In order to achieve equity between staff members, the Management shall prescribe terms
and conditions under which any allowances or related payments shall be made.
The Management shall establish and operate conditions under which staff members in the
professional categories assigned to a station outside their home country shall be reimbursed
for income tax legally due and paid on their income and benefits derived from their
employment with SFA.
5.2 Establishing Initial Salary
Recruitment can only be undertaken for positions that have already been approved by the
SFA Management, and in the case of temporary staff, approval will be by the Head of Human
Resources according to an agreed budget. Before any new appointment is made, a job
description for that position is prepared by the immediate supervisor and approved by the
Head of Human Resources. In the case of a temporary staff, the appointment can be made
by the Head of Human Resources.
The starting salary for newly hired staff positions will be determined by operational grades.
5.3 Payment of Salary
Salaries will be paid monthly in arrears. All locally recruited staff will have their salaries and
benefits paid in Kenya shillings but budgeted for and denominated in US$. Should the
exchange rate earlier approved by the Finance fluctuate by more than 10 percent of the
market rate, then the Executive Director may seek authority of the Treasurer and the
Secretary to adjust the same accordingly. Expatriate staff will be given an option of having
their salary paid in local currency or in US Dollars.
These regulations do not apply to employees recruited through a contract with universities,
or other organizations, and who are paid by their parent organization.
5.4 Statutory Deductions
SFA will make monthly tax deductions from the gross salary and all taxable benefits and
allowances of local employees and will pay these deductions in accordance with local laws
as amended from time to time. These include any fixed contribution prescribed by the laws
for payment towards any national social security scheme or its equivalent.
Statutory deductions as provided for by the legislation of the Government of Kenya include
the following: Pay-As-You-Earn (PAYE), National Social Security Fund (NSSF), National
Hospital Insurance Fund (NHIF), and any other levy that may, from time to time, implemented
by the government. These are reviewed regularly to be consistent with legislation.
SFA shall also make such other deductions as may be required by the laws of the host country
or as may be agreed upon for staff welfare, cooperative savings, and similar funds and for
debts owed to SFA by individuals.
5.5 Non Statutory Deductions
Contributions of staff members, who are participants in a pension scheme, shall be
deducted each pay period from the total payments due to them.
5.6 Salary Advances
SFA strongly discourages salary advance requests and will only grant them for
emergencies or exceptions noted below. A request for a salary advance must be submitted
in writing to the Head of Human Resources. Salary advances may be made under the
following circumstances and conditions:
• Upon departure, for extended official travel or for approved leave, involving absence
from the duty station for one or more pay days, up to the amount that would fall due
for payment during the anticipated period of absence.
• When a staff member fails to receive his regular payment through no fault of his own;
• Upon separation, where final settlement of pay accounts cannot be made at the time
of departure, subject to the advance not exceeding 80 percent of the estimated final
net payments due;
• When a newly appointed staff member arrives without sufficient funds;
• Upon initial appointment of staff in professional category or change of duty station to
another country.
An advance may be authorized for other reasons, taking account of the prevailing conditions
of employment in the locality of SFA office concerned. Salary advance will be recovered at a
rate determined at the time the advance is authorized commencing the same month in which
the advance is made. Deduction of the salary advance is one off pay from the employee
salary.
5.7 Change in Job Description
Any Foundation employee who is appointed to a new position within the organization, which
carries significantly increased levels of responsibility, is entitled to a salary review at the time
of his/her new appointment. Similarly, if during any one of the annual performance evaluation
periods, it is determined that the employee has been assigned and has undertaken
significantly increased level of responsibility, the employee is entitled to a salary review at the
time of his or her appointment.
Once salary review is finalized and new job descriptions are agreed upon, the salary increase
commensurate with the increase in responsibility will be effective as determined by
management where applicable.
5.8 Cost of Living Adjustment
Cost of living adjustments (COLA) may be considered, for all staff, if it is determined by the
management that the local conditions have changed considerably and have strongly eroded
the purchasing power of the employee’s current salary. COLA will be recommended based
on changes documented in the most recent Central Bureau of Statistics (CBS) annual inflation
data or the most current report on the same prepared by the Central Bank or the Ministry of
Finance. Every effort will be made to make COLA adjustments that are consistent with the
practices of comparator organizations.
5.9 Compensatory Time/Overtime
Overtime is defined as any time worked in excess of the normal number of hours per week
or worked on Saturdays, Sundays, statutory public holidays or on the employee’s normal
rest day. Overtime can only be earned if extra hours worked were done to:
• Cover an emergency that is work not done by an absent employee or work, which
would if not done disrupt the services.
• To provide essential staffing where vacancies exist.
• To perform a heavy volume of work of a temporary nature in the implementation of an
approved programme.
• To perform work that cannot be performed during normal working hours without
disrupting normal services.
• To provide essential services to the organisation over and above the normal working
hours.
All overtime must be authorized in advance by the Line Managers or Executive Director who
will also have to justify that the overtime constitutes the best means of meeting the situation.
Any overtime earned shall not exceed 50% of the employees’ normal working time in any one
month.
5.10 Claims and Payments
The right of a staff member to claim any allowance, grant or payment existing but unpaid,
shall lapse one year after the date on which the entitlement arose and as long as the project
under which the payment was being drawn is still running.
The right of SFA to claim from a staff member any overpayment made and received in good
faith shall lapse one year after such overpayment was made. Claims by staff members for
entitlements not received and by SFA for the refund of overpayments shall be submitted in
writing.
SFA normally takes no action to pay staff members, or to recover from them, balances in
amounts of US$5 or less. Staff members wishing to file claims in such amounts are entitled
to do so.
6 EMPLOYEE BENEFITS
Definitions:
For the purposes of this policy, the following definitions apply:
A staff member‘s authorised dependents are dependents of an employee who in any year
permanently reside with the employee, and may include, as supported by relevant legal proof:
a. For purposes of this Manual, a ‘Spouse’ is one legal wife or husband. ‘Spouse’ is
defined in accordance with applicable State law.
b. Up to 4 dependents of an employee over whom the staff member and spouse or
partner has legal custody, and may include, as supported by relevant legal proof,
biological, adopted, foster and step children up to 24 years of age.
c. A staff member becomes eligible for all benefits immediately after joining the
organization
6.1 Pension (Retirement Benefits)
Staff members shall be entitled to 12 percent of their basic pay as pension benefits. Pension
provisions for support staff shall take into account the prevailing conditions of employment in
the locality of the SFA office concerned and applicable national legislation.
6.2 Group Life Insurance Cover/Group Personal Accident/ Travel Insurance
Staff members shall participate in SFA Life Insurance Plan providing life insurance benefits,
accidental, death, dismemberment and disability benefits as per the insurance policy in place.
Group Life Insurance is renewable annually and ceases upon completion of employment with
SFA. SFA pays the full premium cost of health care insurance, group life insurance, and group
accident insurance. Group life insurance is provided by SFA through insurance company
sought competitively through procurement.
A staff member becomes eligible for group life insurance and personal accident insurance
immediately upon starting employment at SFA. For life insurance, in case of death of a
member, his/her beneficiaries would receive three times the staff member's annual salary for
the Group Life Insurance and five times the staff member’s annual salary for the Group
Personal Accident.
On recruitment, staff should provide the Head of Human Resources with the name and
address of the next of kin and specify the beneficiary/beneficiaries of life and other death
benefits. The names of the nominees (beneficiaries) can be revised by the Staff periodically
as they deem fit. The revised names should be forwarded to HR at every point of change.
6.3 Medical Insurance
All Staff members, their legal spouse and up to four dependent children shall participate in
an SFA medical insurance plan providing benefits for hospital expenses, medical services
and prescribed drugs and medicines.
If staff members prefer to use other doctors/chemists other than the medical insurance
accredited etc. they should settle the bills and request reimbursement from the existing
medical insurance.
6.4 Burial Benefit
The Foundation will cover up to KShs. 100,000 for the burial expenses. In addition, the
Foundation will also be responsible for transportation of the deceased staff member or
dependant to the burial site. The staff member should complete the All Purpose Beneficiary
Form at the time of appointment. The staff member is responsible for keeping this form up to
date and making any changes in designation of beneficiary as appropriate.
6.5 Education Allowance
Reimbursement of education expenses for up to four dependent children under the age of
24 of staff members will be subject to an annual limit determined by the Management on an
annual basis.
6.6 Transport
The use of personal vehicles for office business is discouraged. Staff members should be
able to apply for (from the logistics office) and obtain office transport or be authorized by the
Head of Human Resources to use a taxi service. For this purpose, driving to and from work
in one’s personal vehicle is not considered official.
When a staff member needs transport during office hours for official purposes, he/she should
fill out a transport request form and submit it to the HR Department at the earliest opportunity.
The request should be submitted before the end of the preceding day if transport is required
early the next morning, or before 10 am or if it is required for the afternoon of the same day.
If a long trip is involved, then requests should come in as soon as the details of the trip are
known, and at least three working days before the intended trip so that adequate
arrangements can be made.
No transport requests should be made directly to the Driver(s) unless prior arrangements
have been made with the administrative office. In the event that office transport is not
available and the use of a personal vehicle for official business is authorised by the Head of
Human Resources, then the staff member can claim reimbursement of expenses on the basis
of a mileage rate equivalent to what AA (Kenya) has published to cover fuel costs, wear and
tear and insurance costs. There will be no further liability on the part of SFA in the event of
any accident or loss while the personal vehicle is used for official business.
6.7 Passports and Visas
SFA will reimburse staff for reasonable costs incurred in obtaining passports and necessary
visas for authorized travel. When a staff has renewed or obtained her/his passport on her/his
own, SFA refunds the cost of renewal on the staff member’s first international trip.
6.8 Details and Administration of Staff Benefits
SFA values the well-being of its staff, and provides the benefits to staff included in this Manual
However, the benefit programmes described here may be reviewed and modified from time
to time at the sole discretion of SFA. Only brief descriptions of various benefits are included
in this Manual Comprehensive summaries are available in the offices of the Head of Human
Resources. All staff members are encouraged to consult these summaries and other relevant
documents for details of coverage, eligibility, exclusions, and other significant provisions.
6.9 Staff Welfare Representation
A Staff Council, elected by and responsible to the staff, shall be established for ensuring
continuing contact between the staff and the Executive Director with respect to the terms and
conditions of the staff and general staff welfare. The Council shall be entitled to make
proposals to the Executive Director in this regard.
The Council shall be composed in such a way as to afford equitable representation of all
levels of the staff and shall operate under statutes approved by the Executive Committee.
Except for instructions to meet on emergencies, which may require immediate action and
thereby preclude prior consultation, general administrative instructions, or direction on
question are transmitted in advance to the Staff Council for consideration and comment
before being placed in effect.
Any member of the staff who has an appointment of one year or more or who has completed
one year of service shall be eligible for election to the Staff Council, if their service with SFA
is reasonably expected to continue throughout the period for which they would be elected to
serve the Council. Staff members who have appointments of one year or more, or who have
completed their probation period shall be eligible to participate in the voting for members of
the Staff Council.
7 ATTENDANCE AND LEAVE BENEFITS
7.1 Attendance
7.1.1 Official Work Week and Working Hours
The Foundation's normal workweek begins on Monday through to Friday.
The Kenya Employment Act sets the minimum workweek for regular full-time salaried
employees at forty (40) hours. Administrative and departmental offices will be open from 8:00
am to 5:00 pm Monday through Thursday and 8:00am to 2:00pm on Friday, except on
designated holidays.
Driver(s), guards and the Office Assistant(s) have longer working hours due to the nature of
their work. However, a Driver who does not have any errands to run after 5 p.m. may go home
at that time.
During working hours employees should devote themselves exclusively to the discharge of
their duties. Employees are asked to discourage personal visitors and telephone calls from
friends and relatives during working hours.
Punctuality and regular attendance are essential for SFA to operate effectively. If a staff
member is delayed in the morning or unable to come to work, the Head of Human Resources,
or the staff member’s direct supervisor must be notified as close to the regular starting time
as possible. This information must be entered on the leave management system.
Unnecessary absenteeism and lateness can lead to disciplinary action up to and including
termination. If an employee reports to work late, s/he is expected to inform her/his supervisor
within 30 minutes of normal starting time.
Different work schedules may be subject to call on a standby basis for emergencies, special
events, and in unusual circumstances. The regular hours will, however, be compensated after
consultation with the supervisor and approval from the Head of Human Resources. Staff
members shall be expected to make themselves available for work beyond normal working
hours when such circumstances demand.
7.1.2 Rest Periods
Employees are entitled to a maximum of a 1 hour lunch period. Work load permitting, a rest
period of not more than fifteen (15) minutes during the first half of a regular workday and not
more than fifteen (15) minutes during the second half of a regular workday is permitted for
full time employees.
Rest periods cannot be accumulated for use later nor used to shorten the regular workday or
lengthen the lunch period.
7.2 Leave of Absence
7.2.1 Leave Eligibility
Foundation staff become legible for leave benefit when they join the organization. The
accumulation of leave and pay for eligible fixed term part-time staff members will be on a
prorated basis. Upon leaving the organization, an employee of SFA will be paid the
accumulated leave days for that year this is subject to approval from the supervisor.
Leave With Pay
In order for a staff member to be eligible for pay when absent from work, s/he must qualify in
accordance with the provisions of the appropriate policy outlined below relating to Annual
Leave, Holidays, Sick Leave, Maternity Leave, Paternity Leave and Special Leave.
Leave Without Pay
Foundation staff may be allowed leave of absence without pay for a maximum period of up
to three consecutive months. A leave without pay is for a reason not specifically referred to
in one of the policies herein covering absences with pay. Any absence of this nature is
considered ‘leave of absence without pay’ in accordance with the provisions of this policy.
Leave without pay will only be granted in exceptional cases to employees who have been
employed with SFA for a minimum of twelve months. This can only be granted if it does not
disrupt the Foundation’s plans over the period of the leave. Staff who wish to take this form
of leave should apply to the Executive Director at least two months before commencement of
the leave.
7.2.2 Annual Leave
Annual leave shall accrue at the rate of one point seven five (1.75) of a working day per
calendar month, while the staff member is in full pay status. Annual leave may be taken in
units of days or half days. All leave arrangements shall be subject to the exigencies of service,
which may require that a staff member take leave at a time designated by the supervisor.
Leave may be taken only when authorized, though personal circumstances and preferences
of the individual staff member shall, as far as possible, be considered.
For purposes of annual leave, leave year will run from 1 January to the last day of December.
A leave record must be maintained for each staff member who is informed of his or her leave
balance at the end of the leave year.
Subject to directives issued by the Executive Director, annual leave may be accumulated
from year to year. However, not more than 5 working days of such leave may be carried
forward beyond the last day of December of any year subject to approval.
Staff members may, in exceptional circumstances, be granted advance annual leave up to a
maximum of one week, provided that their service is expected to continue for the period
necessary to accrue the leave so advanced.
7.2.3 Public Holidays
A public holiday can only be taken after confirmation that indeed the government has either
announced or gazetted this day as an official public holiday. When a holiday falls on a Sunday,
the following Monday is observed. Official holidays occurring during a vacation period are not
counted against vacation time.
7.2.4 Sick Leave
7.2.4.1 Entitlements
Paid sick leave during the probation period is limited to 5 working days. After completion of
the probation period, all full-time staff members are entitled sick leave with full pay.
Medical leave is to be charged during all periods of absence of the staff member from his/her
customary workplace for medical reasons--such as to take an annual medical exam, keep a
doctor’s appointment, provide care for a family member who is ill, etc. All time charged to
medical leave should be recorded; and may be in increments of 30 minutes or one hour, if
less than a full 8-hour workday is required. Sick leave request forms must be submitted at the
earliest opportunity, otherwise absences are charged to personal leave or annual leave.
Regular attendance is regarded as an important part of job performance. Staff members who
abuse sick leave by taking sick days when they are not ill would find their salaries and annual
appraisals negatively affected. Poor attendance or repeated abuse of sick leave may result
in termination of employment.
If a member of staff is unable to work due to illness, he/she should make sure his/her direct
supervisor or the Head of Human Resources is informed at the earliest opportunity. For illness
necessitating absence from work for more than 1 consecutive working days, a doctor's
certificate for the full number of days of absence must accompany the leave request, and
additional certificates must be sent in weekly during the continuance of illness. Failure to
provide such certificates results in the absence being charged against annual leave and/or
being treated as unpaid leave.
Staff members can draw on their sick leave for the illness of a member of the immediate
family (spouse, son, daughter, parent, brother, sister)
Sick leave does not accrue into the following year if not utilized in the current year.
An absence approved as annual leave may be converted to sick leave if a staff member falls
ill during his/her leave. A medical certificate for the full number of days of absence should be
submitted. This certificate must be provided even if the period is less than two days.
If a staff member is forced to use all of his/her sick leave days because of disability due to
serious illness or injury and is still medically unable to return to work, extended sick leave with
full pay may be authorized for a period up to the number of days of sick leave the staff member
had available at the onset of the illness or disability.
If the staff member is still unable to return to work at the end of this period, the Executive
Director may grant a further sick leave at 75% of salary up to the number of days that, added
to the sick leave and extended sick leave already used. A medical opinion from the staff
member's doctor is required for extended sick leave. A second medical opinion by an SFA -
appointed doctor may be required before deciding on an extension, and this could result in a
recommendation for medical discharge. The cost of this second opinion is covered by SFA.
Where there is a serious difference of opinion on the medical facts relating to staff member’s
ability to perform his / her duties, or regarding sick leave under these rules, the Executive
Director may, if circumstances warrant it, refer the matter to a Medical Board for advice.
Staff members should inform their supervisor, as soon as possible, of any accident or
sickness occurring while they are on official travel. A medical certification is required if the
incapacity prevents their performance of duties for more than three working days. The facts
must be recorded on the travel expense report form.
7.2.4.3 Special Leave for Extended Illness
The organization may grant special leave with pay to a staff member who exhausts the sick
leave permitted under these rules. Special leave with partial pay to a staff member who,
having exhausted the sick leave permitted under these rules, performs part-time work during
the periods of ill health or injury.
The organization may also grant special leave with partial pay in other cases of temporary
disability, where the normal sick leave entitlement has been fully utilized, and where the return
to active duty of the staff member is anticipated within a reasonably early period. Special
leave, with full or partial pay, may also be granted, as a result of temporary disability, to staff
members who have exhausted their sick leave entitlement and after return from duty, require
additional sick leave.
Staff members shall immediately notify the responsible officer of any case of contagious
disease occurring in the household. Staff members who are directed not to attend the office,
because of these circumstances, shall receive their full salary and other emoluments for the
period of authorized absence.
7.2.5 Maternity Leave
A female staff member who has completed the probation period when maternity leave starts
is entitled to a total of 90 calendar days maternity leave for each confinement leading to a
non-surgical delivery or a miscarriage or abortion, or to 108 calendar days maternity leave for
a Caesarean-section delivery.
Maternity leave must be taken in consecutive months. The female employee can choose to
combine this maternity leave with their unused annual leave days.
An expectant staff member may work as close to delivery as is medically advisable, and may
return to work as soon after delivery as she wishes.
A staff member wishing to stay away from work for longer than the stipulated period in order
to care for the infant may apply for leave without pay. Provided that the total absence does
not exceed six months, SFA will reinstate the staff member upon return from such extended
leave:
• In the same position occupied at the time she commenced maternity leave, or
• In a comparable position with salary and benefits equivalent to those to which she was
entitled at the beginning of maternity leave.
If medical complications of pregnancy require additional leave, this may be taken as sick
leave. Maternity leave may be taken in part before and in part after delivery. Applications for
maternity leave must include a medical certificate from a qualified medical practitioner, which
indicates the estimated dates of confinement.
7.2.6 Paternity leave
Paternity leave is absence from duty with pay available to a male staff member in connection
with the adoption of a child aged less than six years or delivery of his wife's child.
Paternity leave shall amount to 10 straight days for each birth or adoption, and must be
consumed within three months of birth or adoption.
7.2.7 Adoption Leave
All staff members who have completed 12 months of service are allowed up to 7 working days
of paid leave to facilitate legal adoption of a child.
In addition, a full-time female staff member who has successfully completed the probation
period and who legally adopts an infant (aged 1 year or below) is entitled to a total of 90
calendar days of maternity leave. Male staff are entitled to the paternity leave upon adoption
of a child.
Leave for adoption purposes is normally granted only for a continuous period immediately
following the assumption of custody of the child by the staff member.
All legal documents relating to the adoption should be submitted to the office of Head of
Human Resources to ensure that the child is entitled to receive all benefits enjoyed by eligible
dependants.
7.2.7 Compassionate Leave
All staff are entitled to compassionate leave in the event of the serious illness or death of
an immediate member of the staff member's family (parents, parents-in-law, brothers or
sisters). Compassionate leave provides for up to five working days of paid leave, plus travel
time by the most direct routing. All time over the five days plus travel time must be charged
to annual leave, or taken as leave without pay.
International staff outside their recognized home base will, in addition, be provided one round
trip economy air ticket between the duty station and the stricken family member. The trip
must take the most direct routing, and must not exceed the cost of travel between duty station
and home base.
Staff are entitled to a maximum of 10 working days in the event of death of a spouse or child.
Compassionate leave cannot be accumulated, and is not carried over to subsequent years.
Absence from work relating to the death or illness of anyone else is charged against annual
or personal leave.
7.2.8 Special Leave
Special leave with full or partial pay or without pay may be granted for:
• Advanced study or research in the interest of SFA;
• Cases of extended illness; or
• Other important reasons as the Executive Director determines.
If the leave is to last more than 14 consecutive days, the conditions of the leave, the status
of benefits, and the terms and conditions of the return to work must be in writing between
the employee and Executive Director.
Should an employee fail to return to work at the expiration of the leave, the employee may
be terminated unless other arrangements have been made.
7.2.9 Absence without Authorisation
If, for compelling reasons, a staff member is unable to report for duty, he/she must advise
the immediate supervisor the reason for his/her absence as soon as possible, and in any
case within 24 hours. An unreported or insufficiently justified absence will be considered as
unauthorised absence.
Absence without leave or permission, including overstaying for two weeks after the expiry of
authorised leave, will result in automatic termination of employment. The staff member will
be treated as having abandoned or vacated his/her position with SFA.
7.2.10 Flexible Working Arrangements
SFA expects staff to be at their duty station during standard working hours. However, SFA
accepts that, on occasions, staff may need to vary working hours and/or location for either
personal or professional needs. Staff may take short breaks to attend to urgent personal
matters in consultation with the Supervisor.
However, four flexi-time options are available: 7.00am – 4.00pm, 7:30am–4:30pm, 8.00am -
5.00pm and 8:30am–5.30pm, with a one hour lunch break. The approval of these times is
dependent upon the supervisor’s assessment of the work load in the program/department.
The decision to alter a staff member’s official work week must be communicated in writing to
HR by the staff, copied to the supervisor/unit head. It is the responsibility of the unit head to
monitor the attendance schedules and report to HR any abuse of the same.
Personal needs that may require significant time periods should be obtained with formal
application and approval of leave.
SFA is prepared to consider alternatives to standard working hours and/or working from
an alternative location, where the alternative arrangements:
a. Are advantageous to both SFA and the staff member;
b. Do not impair SFA productivity; and
c. Are short-term and temporary
It is the responsibility of the unit head to monitor the attendance schedules and report to HR
any abuse of the same. In addition, consideration will be given to “customised flexi-time”
which is a response to unique work environments or personal circumstances that require
flexi time outside these already approved schedules, up to a maximum of six months. This
option must be approved by the supervisor and HR. Any future changes to approved flexi
time hours must be communicated to HR in writing.
8 GRIEVANCE RESOLUTION
8.1 Grievance Resolution
Grievance is a statement of dissatisfaction, usually by an individual or management,
concerning the interpretation or application of a provision of policy or regulation, direction or
other instrument made or issued by the Employer dealing with the terms or conditions of
employment, disciplinary action, dismissal and letters of discipline. The aim of the procedure
is to settle the grievance at its point of origin and to apply the principles of natural justice
(procedural fairness).
A firmly established principle of natural justice is that no person should be condemned
without recourse to defence. SFA believes that all staff members should be treated fairly
and equitably. Where staff grievances arise, SFA tries to achieve resolutions that are
acceptable and reasonable to all parties. The three principles of procedural fairness are
• The hearing rule requires a decision maker to give an opportunity to be heard to a
person whose interests will be adversely affected by the decision;
• The bias rule requires a decision maker to be disinterested or unbiased in the matter
to be decided on;
• The no evidence rule requires that a decision be based on evidence (Comment: Is the
Evidence rule or the No Evidence Rule? Not quite sure, need to verify)
In summary, every respondent to a complaint has the right (where there may be detriment
arising from the resolution of that complaint) to be heard and to present provable evidence
and submissions in one’s own cause, and the opportunity to be heard promptly by an impartial
decision maker.
Employees are encouraged to discuss problems with their supervisors first, because
supervisors can usually resolve these problems. Employees who have differences with their
supervisors or co-workers may seek help from another staff member or Management. SFA
recognises that in some circumstances formal procedures may need to be followed. Staff
members have the right to appeal against a grievance outcome.
If an employee approaches a supervisor or a co-worker with a work-related problem, the coworker or the supervisor should listen carefully, discuss possible solutions and follow through
to ensure action is taken. If need to investigate arises, the supervisor should promptly inform
the employee of this, usually within a week. If there is delay, the employee should be kept
informed about the status and reasons for the delay. An employee not satisfied with the
answer provided can approach management.
8.1.1 Informal Grievance Resolution Procedure:
This is an informal process that stops at any time the employee is satisfied. This approach
provides additional opportunities to keep minor problems from becoming major headaches
for everyone involved.
a. Talk to immediate supervisor; if not satisfied
b. Talk to the Head of Human Resources, if not satisfied
c. Talk to the Executive Director.
8.1.2 Formal Grievance Resolution Procedure
If a matter is not resolved to the satisfaction of the grievant in an informal manner, the
grieving employee should then resort to the formal approach which is outlined below:
1. The employee must, within ten (10) working days of the event or occurrence which
is the subject of the grievance, present the grievance in writing to the Department
Head specifying the name(s) of the person(s) involved, the date(s) of the
incident(s) in question, and a description of the offending conduct. This formal
complaint must be filed within six (6) months of the most recent incident.It is
indicated that complain must be given in writing within 10 working days of the
occurrence of the event and again it is stated that formal complaint must be filed
within six months of occurrence of the most recent event).
2. Within seven (7) calendar days of the receipt of a formal complaint, the Department
Head will initiate an investigation, of the facts and circumstances of the alleged
incident. In this investigation, the Department Head may contact one or more
offices of the Foundation and ask to review portions of their record. Foundation
employees are to make a good faith effort to comply with such requests in a timely
manner. In such investigation, the Department Head seeks to determine that: (a)
the incidents described in the complaint cannot be dismissed as incredible on their
face, and; (b) the incidents as described would constitute a violation of SFA policy.
At the conclusion of this review the Department Head prepares a report which
either calls for a formal hearing or dismisses the complaint. While there is no set
time in which an investigation must be completed, the Department Head will
attempt to conclude it as promptly as possible. The report will be sent to the
complainant, the Foundation employee against whom the grievance was brought,
and the Executive Director. A good faith effort shall be made to assure that this
report is treated confidentially.
3. An employee who is not satisfied with the investigating officer’s decision should
write to the Executive Director indicating this, and await a decision.
4. An employee who further not satisfied with the decision of the Executive Director
may appeal for hearing with the Management of the Foundation.
8.2 Disciplinary Measures
The Executive Director may impose disciplinary measures on staff members whose conduct
is unsatisfactory. He/she may summarily dismiss a member of staff for serious misconduct.
Summary dismissal also occurs where an employee is guilty of:
1. Serious misconduct inconsistent with the fulfilment of the expressed or implied
conditions of his or her contract of employment such that it would be unreasonable to
continue the employment relationship.
2. Habitual or substantial neglect of duties
3. Lack of skills that the employee expressly or by implication made the employer believe
he or she possessed
4. Wilful disobedience or insubordination.
5. Absence from work at least three times without permission of the employer and without
a reasonable excuse
6. Theft or intentional damage of company property or other employees’ property
7. Assault on any other employee.
8. Falsifying official records.
9. Destruction or theft of official records or release of confidential information.
10. Reporting to work under the influence of alcohol or drugs or drinking alcohol or using
illicit drugs within the SFA premises. Exceptions to this rule may apply where a party
is held within SFA premises and alcoholic drinks are served.
11. Gambling on company property.
12. Sexual harassment
13. When one is out of official duty station and acts in a way that brings disrepute to SFA.
14. Any other criminal offence under Kenyan Law
Disciplinary measures, imposed by the Executive Director upon staff members whose
conduct is unsatisfactory, shall consist alternatively of written censure, suspension without
pay, demotion or dismissal for misconduct, provided that suspension pending investigation
shall not be considered a disciplinary measure.
If a charge of misconduct is made against a staff member and the Executive Director so
decides, the staff member may be suspended from duty, with or without pay, pending
investigations, the suspension will not be considered to be part of disciplinary action. It will
only be undertaken to pave way for unbiased investigation.
8.3 Appeals
The Executive Director shall establish an Appeals Committee to advise him/her in cases of
appeal by individual staff members, regarding a grievance arising out of disciplinary action or
against an administrative decision, which the staff member alleges to be in conflict, either in
substance or in form, with the terms of their appointment or with any pertinent staff regulation
and/or administrative/legal directive.
The Appeals Committee shall consist of a Chairperson, and alternate Chairperson, appointed
by the Chairperson of the Management, two members elected from the Staff Council and two
members nominated by the Executive Director. If the Chairperson and the alternate
Chairperson are unavailable, the remainder of the Committee may select an ad hoc
Chairperson. Members of the Appeals Committee shall be of either SFA staff or the Executive
Committee.
Staff members shall have a final right of appeal to the Executive Management Committee
against decisions made by the Executive Director under the appeals procedure established
in accordance with the provisions of this Manual.
Proceedings of the Committee shall require the presence of five members. The Chair of the
Appeals Committee, at the request of either party, may disqualify any member from the
consideration of a specific appeal if, in his / her opinion, such action is warranted.
In cases of termination or other action on grounds of relative efficiency or of inefficiency, the
Committee shall not consider the substantive question of efficiency, but only evidence that
the decision has been motivated by prejudice or by some other extraneous factor.
Action based on the expiration of an appointment by its own terms is not disciplinary in
character nor may such action form the basis of grievance.
The Committee shall determine its own jurisdiction in cases when its competence is in doubt.
The Appeals Committee may make recommendations to the Executive Director if it should
desire to change the procedures regarding appeals as set forth in this Manual. Such
recommendations shall be communicated by the Executive Director to the Staff Council in
order to enable that body to submit its own proposals.
8.3.1 Procedures of the Appeals Committee
Staff members who wish to lodge an appeal shall state their case in a letter to the Executive
Director, through the Departmental Head. In the case of an appeal against an administrative
decision, or a disciplinary action, the letter shall be dispatched to the Executive Director within
two weeks of receipt of the notification of the decision disputed.
If the staff member wishes to make an appeal against the answer received from the Executive
Director or if no reply has been received from the Executive Director, within the two following
weeks, submit his appeal, in writing to the Chair of the Appeals Committee, through the
Secretary of that Committee.
Committee proceedings shall begin within two weeks of receipt of the case and shall proceed
as rapidly as is consistent with a fair review of the issues being considered. Legal counsel
shall be provided to the Committee upon its request.
The Committee shall take any evidence which it considers relevant and shall have authority
to call staff members and to examine any pertinent documents.
Staff members who lodge an appeal shall have access to all pertinent documents in their
personnel file and any other documents considered by the Committee.
Staff members may designate another staff member to present their case or act as their
counsel.
The Committee shall, by majority vote, adopt and submit a report to the Executive Director
within three weeks after completion of the hearings. The Committee may extend this time
limit in exceptional circumstances.
The report shall be considered as constituting a record of the proceedings in the appeal, and
may include a summary of the matter as well as the Committee’s recommendation.
9 ADMINSTRATIVE PROCEDURES
A comprehensive SFA finance manual is in use and will be referred to under issues
involving financial matters.
