9.1 Petty Cash
As described in the SFA Finance Manual, petty cash fund is used for small cash purchases
of office supplies, taxi expenses and other immediate purchasing needs. The Accountant
keeps the fund and makes requests for reimbursements. Receipts for purchases should be
submitted according to protocol described in the Finance Manual.
9.2 Telephone Use
SFA provides a central telephone system for making local or official international calls. All
international calls are to be recorded in the telephone book by date, number dialed, and
projects. Because of the large volume of telephone usage for Foundation business, personal
mobile or international telephone use is discouraged. However whenever allowed, such calls
must be documented, paid for by the caller and be as brief as possible.
9.3 E-Mail and Internet
All staff members are expected to obtain the SFA e-mail account subject to approval advice
from Head of Human Resources. Once they have obtained e-mail addresses, staff members
are expected to be courteous and respectful to others in the presentation of the e-mail.
SFA provides its employees with access to the internet and its email system to assist them
in the performance of their duties. Their use should primarily be for official company business;
however, minimal personal use of the internet and company email is permitted, provided the
user complies with the provisions contained in IT and Computer Use Policy Guide for Staff.
a) Personal use of the email system or surfing of the internet should never impact the normal
flow of business related email and network traffic. SFA reserves the right to ask its mailbox
hosts to purge identifiable personal email to preserve the integrity of the email systems,
and to restrict the access of specific individuals to the internet should their use be judged
excessive.
b) The viewing, creation or transmission by any employee, consultant or contractor of any
offensive, obscene or indecent images, data or other restricted material by email or on
the internet is prohibited, whether or not this is done during office hours. Anyone found
to have done so will be subject to disciplinary action. Examples of prohibited material
include, but are not limited to:
• Sexually explicit messages, images, cartoons, or jokes;
• Unwelcome propositions, requests for dates, or love letters;
• Profanity, obscenity, slander, or libel;
• Ethnic, religious, or racial slurs;
• Political beliefs or commentary;
• Terrorism, terrorist activities, inciting or condoning violence or vandalism;
• Any other activity considered illegal in the country of origin/receipt.
It is recognized that websites which display material of a pornographic or offensive nature, or
which contain malware designed to infect and harm your computer, may be accidentally
accessed from time to time. Should this happen and you become concerned for the integrity
of your computer and/or network access, inform the IT officer immediately and discontinue
use of your system, closing down all shared drives. Remedial action will be taken as
necessary to protect your computer and SFA’ IT systems from further infection.
The forwarding of chain-letters is strictly forbidden – this includes those purporting to be for
Charity or other good causes as well as those promising wealth or other personal gain.
Likewise, no non-business-related messages of any kind should be sent to multiple external
destinations as this is considered ‘spamming’, an illegal activity in many countries.
Email should not be used to send large attached files, and a strict limit of 25Mb has been
applied by the mailbox host. In addition, many email systems will not accept large files which
may be returned and result in the overloading of the SFA email system. The Foundation has
active email security protocols to screen for malicious content; even so, employees are
recommended to exercise caution when opening all attachments, particularly if the file
extension is not recognized.
The SFA reserves the right to monitor employees’ email and internet usage, including
intercepting emails before they are read, and accessing personal internet browser history for
the purpose of investigating unauthorised use of the SFA’ telecommunication system,
preventing or detecting crime, or ascertaining compliance with this Policy. This will include
personal emails where appropriate.
All monitoring will be authorised by the Executive Director of SFA. Any information obtained
during monitoring will be kept strictly confidential and will be used only for the purpose for
which the monitoring has taken place.
Downloading of Information
SFA Staff should be aware that before any information is downloaded, a staff member should:
▪ Check the legality of downloading the information, particularly with respect to copyright
permission. If in doubt of the legality, staff members should contact the IT administrator
on IP matters for advice.
▪ Be aware that many Internet sites maintain records of who accesses (or visits) them
and what, if anything, they download from the site.
▪ Not download unlicensed software or violate limitations on the use of software as
imposed by any license agreements.
▪ Before installing downloaded software on their workstations, first verify with the IT
Administrator that the software has been obtained from a reputable source.
SFA staff should refer to the “IT and Computer Use Policy Guide for Staff” for further details.
Failure to comply with the provisions outlined in the Policy Guide will lead to appropriate
reprimand. Any action judged to constitute gross misconduct may lead to summary dismissal
at the discretion of the Executive Director.
9.4 SFA Property
Employees are expected to exercise due care when using company property and to use such
property only for authorised purposes. Employees are accountable for equipment assigned
to them. Property of SFA issued to an employee must be returned at the time of termination
of employment or when requested by a supervisor. An employee may use, on a temporary
basis, some specific facility at home when the need arises and subject to prior approval of
the Executive Director.
9.5 Locking Up
The SFA office administrator is responsible for opening and closing the office. However, all
staff members are requested to ensure they have locked their windows and that their
respective machines, and light switches are turned off. In cases where a staff member stays
late or works during weekends, he/she is responsible for locking up the office. In addition to
signing an attendance register in the custody of the Security Staff at the gate.
9.6 Entitlements
9.6.1 Travel and Transfer Expenses
In conformity with the principles approved by the MC, the Management shall determine
conditions under which the travel and removal costs of staff members and when appropriate,
their spouse and dependent children, shall be paid by SFA.
The SFA will not make any contribution in full or in part, any payment of travel, removal or
related expenses for staff members, their spouse and dependent children, provided for in
accordance with the provisions of this Manual, if payment for the same purpose is received
from a source external to SFA. These expenses will not be paid by SFA if they are already
being paid by another organization.
9.6.2 Staff Relocation and Repatriation Costs
In conformity with the principles approved by the SMT, the Management shall determine
conditions under which the travel and removal costs of staff members and when appropriate,
their spouse and dependent children, shall be paid by SFA.
The SFA will not make any contribution in full or in part, any payment of travel, removal or
related expenses for staff members, their spouse and dependent children, provided for in
accordance with the provisions of this Manual, if payment for the same purpose is received
from a source external to SFA. These expenses will not be paid by SFA if they are already
being paid by another organization.
SFA shall pay the travel expenses of staff members as follows:
• Appointment travel: On initial appointment of staff in the professional categories to the
duty station, when, at the time of appointment they were not residing within commuting
distance of the duty station.
• Mission Travel: When required to travel on duty to a place outside commuting distance
of the duty station to carry out official business.
Travel expenses for eligible family members are payable only if they are to remain at the staff
member’s duty station for at least six months.
Subject to the conditions laid down in this Manual, SFA shall pay, upon request of the staff
member, the travel expenses of their spouse and dependent children as follows:
• On the initial appointment of the staff member, when at the time of appointment, they
were not residing within commuting distance of the duty station, if the appointment is
for one year or longer.
• Following completion by staff member’s contract of not less than one year of
continuous service.
9.6.3 Points of Origin and Return
Appointment travel to the duty station is paid from the place of recruitment or from any other
place, if the cost does not exceed that payable from either of the two proceeding places.
Travel shall be authorised in writing on the travel authorisation form and sufficiently in
advance of the day of departure to enable all travel documents to be obtained. Staff members
shall be personally responsible for ascertaining that they have the proper authorisation before
commencing travel for themselves and eligible family members.
9.6.4 Route Mode and Standard Transport.
Air travel, by the most direct and economical route, is regarded as the normal mode for all
official travel except when clearly applicable. For long and arduous journeys by air or for
medical travel, the Executive Director may authorise business class travel in line with the
grant conditions.
Travel rest periods and stopovers are granted to staff members as follows, subject to the
exigencies of the service, for journeys by air:
• If the scheduled time is between six and ten hours, they will not be required to
commence duty within 12 hours of arriving at their destination.
• If the scheduled time is more than ten but not more than 18 hours they will not be
required to commence duty within 24 hours of arriving at their destination, or SFA may
grant a stopover not exceeding 24 hours.
Travel by car may be authorised at the request of the staff member, subject to the conditions
laid down in this Manual and provided that the traveller holds adequate car insurance against
damage or injury involving the persons or property of third parties, including passengers and
provides evidence to this effect. SFA accepts no liability for loss or damage to private cars
used for the travel. Costs of authorised travel by car on appointment or transfer can be
reimbursed as follows:
• For the staff member or spouse or for both if travelling together, the cost to SFA of
one economy air fare for the same journey and if applicable, rail/ bus fare to the
nearest airport.
• For every additional authorised and eligible family member travelling by car, 50
percent of the costs, which SFA would have paid had the travel been by air.
• Travel on duty by private car authorised in the interest of SFA is reimbursed at current
Kenya Automobile Association rates.
Travel by sea may be authorised at a standard next below first class. Travel by rail may be
authorised, at first class standard, for all staff in the professional category. The standard by
rail travel for support staff will be decided by the responsible officer according to the
circumstances.
When deviations are made from an approved travel itinerary, SFA liability is limited to the
maximum expenses and travel time to which the staff member would have been entitled if
travel had been carried out by the approved route, mode and standard of transportation.
9.6.5 Accommodation
SFA shall provide suitable accommodation costs for the staff and the family for a period of 1
month on bed and breakfast basis from the date of arrival, within the 1 month, there after staff
is expected to look for alternative accommodation at their own cost.
9.6.6 Daily Subsistence Allowance (DSA)
Subject to the conditions stated hereunder, staff members in the professional categories, and
their eligible family members, on authorised SFA travel, receive reimbursement of reasonable
accommodation, laundry, and dry-cleaning costs incurred in form of Daily Subsistence
Allowance (DSA), which comprises the total contribution of SFA towards such charges as
fixed by the management from time to time.
SFA shall provide a daily subsistence allowance to cover meal for a period of 15 days from
date of arrival.
9.6.7 Shipment of Personal and Household Effects
Shipment of personal and household effects is authorised from the staff member’s actual
address, on a door-to-door basis. Shipments are authorised by air and sea in the following
maximum gross weight limits including packing and crating:
Air:
1 Staff member - 300 kgs
2 Spouse - 100 kgs
3 Each dependent child -
50 kgs (subject to maximum of 4
dependants)
Sea: Total of 4 cubic meters(volume) for Employee, Spouse and maximum of 4 dependants.
If a staff member wishes the personal and household effects be sent by surface shipment,
the total cost to SFA shall be limited to the cost of sending the goods by airfreight and any
excess shall be borne by the staff member. Shipments are authorised in the following
circumstances:
• On appointment: for staff members and eligible family members granted appointment
travel, shipment expenses are paid from the place of recruitment.
• On marriage following appointment, for a spouse in respect of whom appointment
travel to the duty station is authorised
• On transfer, for staff members and eligible family members granted transfer travel,
from the staff member’s previous duty station to the new duty station.
Staff members should ensure that shipments on appointment and transfer are effected within
the time limits, which entitle them to duty free importation under the terms of the
Memorandum of Agreement with the country, which they are assigned.
Storage charges for authorised shipment of personal and household effects for a staff
member initially reporting to duty or transferring to another duty station are allowed for 30
days following the arrival of the shipment at the duty station. No such storage charges are
reimbursed upon separation. A request for shipment of personal and household effects is
made on the travel authorisation form and authorised by the Executive Director or delegated
representative.
9.6.8 Transit Insurance Cover
The insurance of the shipment of personal and household effects on appointment and transfer
is arranged by SFA at its expense in respect of goods to the value of US$ 2,500 for each
adult and US$ 500 for each child, subject to an overall limit of US$ 10,000.
The insurance of accompanied baggage, on appointment, transfer, and separation travel,
whether free, alone or excess, will be arranged and covered by staff member.
A staff member whose baggage is insured for less than its full value can claim only that
proportion of the value of any loss or damage which the insured value bears to the full value
of the baggage. Staff members are therefore advised to take additional insurance at their own
expense if they wish to nullify the risk of pro-rating by the insurance. Upon loss or damage,
staff members should notify the airline or other carriers, or authorities involved, and request
claim forms from the insurer.
10. REMOTE WORKING
10.1 Definition
Remote working is a work arrangement that permits an employee to conduct all or some of their
work at an approved alternative worksite such as the home or in office space near to the
employee’s home.
10.2 Purpose
This policy has been developed to protect sensitive or valuable data and maintain the overall
security of SFA data and equipment whilst employees are working remotely. In addition this
policy recognises and defines the duty of care of the SFA to the remote working employees in
regard to their health and SFAety and fair treatment.
Employees must ensure security of information and systems accessed through mobile and
remote working arrangements are given due consideration. This policy emphasises the
importance of staff understanding the SFA’s current Information security policies and
procedures and each individual’s responsibilities in relation to these which must be adhered to
at all times.
This policy and procedure does not form part of any employee’s contract of employment. It may
be amended from time to time with appropriate consultation with staff and management.
10.3 Eligibility and Process
In principle, any job role at the SFA could be considered for remote working. Nevertheless, it is
clearly the case that some activities can only be adequately carried out on-site, whilst others
may be carried out equally or even more effectively at a remote location – usually the
employee’s home.
The Remote Working Policy should not be used as an alternative to caring for dependants. For
application of leave, please refer to the SFA Leave Policy.
10.4. Security
10.4.1 Personal Security
For the maintenance of personal security, the SFA strongly advises against any external work
contacts visiting an employee when they are working at home and that such visits should take
place on the SFA premises wherever possible. For the employee’s own security it is also
recommended that employees who are remote working should:
• Not release any personal data or information to external contacts such as home
address or personal telephone number
• Always ensure that colleagues are aware of the remote working employee’s
whereabouts and that you are able to be contacted within your contractual working
hours.
10.4.2 Security of Equipment and Data
To ensure Safety and security is maintained at all times, a separate allocated room should be
used for remote working, where possible.
SFA provided IT equipment has a range of security measures enabled to make home working
Safer. Do not use personal devices for storing, accessing or transmitting personal or sensitive
information. Further information around the rules and guidance can be found in the SFA’s ICT
Policy.
The SFA Information Security Policy should be adhered to when remote working; this includes
locking a device when not in use, ensuring that data is encrypted in the event of device loss and
not disclosing any passwords, PINs or encryption keys. It is the responsibility of the remote
worker to Safeguard and protect any SFA information that they hold. Remote workers must
have an understanding of digital risks, use secure working practices and apply encryption and
back-up procedures as appropriate. If the remote worker is not confident in this area, they
should seek assistance from the ICT Support team prior to working remotely.
Digital information must only be downloaded or uploaded over a secure connection. WiFi
networks offered to travellers at airports, hotels, coffee shops and on public transport are
generally insecure and extra measures must be taken to Safeguard against information loss.
SFA’s VPN service provides a secure channel for data transfer over insecure networks and
should be used by remote workers when interacting with SFA resources. This includes but is not
limited to use with laptops, tablets and smartphones.
10.5. Health and Safety
The underlying principle of this section is that the standards of care towards remote working
should be equivalent to that of employees working on the SFA’s premises. Therefore, it is
essential that the conduct of SFA business from an employee’s home or elsewhere does not
adversely affect the health and Safety of the individual or others.
It is the duty of the SFA and the employee’s line manager to ensure the equipment and working
practices meet the standards as defined in the occupational health and Safety Act of 2007.
While the SFA has a reasonable duty of care towards an employee’s health and Safety, the
employee undertaking remote working, is expected to take primary responsibility for ensuring
Safe and healthy working conditions whilst working offsite. Employees are encouraged to seek
further advice and guidance on how to set up a remote working workstation. It is the joint
responsibility of the manager and employee to ensure that the employee assessment and
ascertain remote workability.
If in the event, further clarification or advice is needed, the manager and employee should
ensure they consult with HR department.
10.6. Equipment
Prior to commencing remote working, line manager will discuss and agree with the employee,
what equipment and IT requirements will be needed to enable the individual to work effectively
from home. The equipment will remain the property of the SFA at all times.
In the event of SFA equipment malfunctioning or inoperability, the IT department will in the first
instance provide email and telephone support line to assist the remote worker to identify and
remedy the fault. If the fault persists, the IT department will discuss arrangements to recover
and replace equipment at the earliest opportunity.
With regard to the equipment, the remote worker will be expected to:
• Take reasonable care of the equipment;
• Take all reasonable steps to minimize the risk of theft or damage to SFA property
and paperwork whilst these items are away from SFA premises;
• Use it only for work purposes and in accordance with any operating instructions as
defined in the SFA Information Security Policy;
• Comply with software licensing Terms and Conditions;
• Return to the SFA, the equipment at the end of the Remote working arrangement.
10.7. Financial Matters and Insurance
Employees working remotely are responsible for the Safekeeping and protection of SFA-owned
electronic devices that have been issued to them and reasonable care and due diligence must
be taken to prevent or reduce the possibility of loss or theft of SFA-owned devices.
Remote working employees are required to be aware of the environment in which they are
working and apply appropriate common-sense measures to protect SFA-owned equipment and
SFA data on both SFA owned and privately-owned devices in accordance with the SFA’s ICT
Security Policy.
Equipment in transit left in a stationary vehicle must be locked securely out of site. Remote
Working employees will be responsible for the cost of equipment which is damaged or lost due
to their own negligence. It is advisable, for this reason, that remote working employees clarify
whether their personal insurance will cover them for damage or lost due negligence.
Losses of, or damage to, SFA-owned electronic devices may be investigated in accordance with
the SFA’s Disciplinary Policy.
The SFA will not reimburse an employee for costs incurred whilst remote working through the
use of electricity, water bill and other home expenses. A reasonable allowance will be provided
towards covering WI-FI and phone expenses.
Employees will be reimbursed in full for travel expenses wholly, necessarily and exclusively
incurred in the course of the SFA's business. Authorization for such expenses must be
obtained in advance.
For further clarification on the reimbursement of expenses, please refer to the SFA Staff
Expenses Policy.
10.8. Terms and conditions
The underpinning principle is that Remote working employees will be no worse off than officebased employees when conducting their work. For example, remote workers will be eligible to
attend all appropriate training courses in the same way as office-based employees.
Remote working employees maintain their existing terms and conditions of employment apart
from their designated place of work which changes from the SFA office premise to the remote
worker’s defined remote site.
Prior to commencing Remote Working the employee and line manager should agree on the
working pattern of the employee and the times they will be available for contact. The employee
should be made aware by their line manager that they will be required to visit SFA office on
occasion as required by their line manager or department. Desk space will be provided for this
visit.
To ensure the remote working arrangement is effective, an annual review will be conducted by
the line manager to ensure the business needs are met and the arrangement is still efficient.
On an ongoing basis Remote Working agreements will be reviewed at least annually by the
Department to ensure the arrangement continues to meet any change in business demands.
Remote Working agreements may also be reviewed as a result of any team or departmental
changes.
