1.0 PURPOSE
The Science for Africa Foundation (SFA Foundation) appreciates that human capital is the most
important asset for the organization. The SFA Foundation further recognizes that quality staff
development, which provides staff with the opportunity to contribute more effectively by
developing their abilities and skills, is integral to organizational performance and staff morale.
SFA Foundation therefore values and encourages development and improvement of personal
and team skills by creating and enabling an environment for continuous learning and knowledge
sharing and by supporting staff-led initiatives for training and development.
The intention of the Science for Africa Foundation through this policy is to encourage individuals
to manage their own development, with support from their manager to the benefit of the individual
and the organization. Its purpose is:
a) To help individual staff acquire knowledge, skills and understanding which will allow them to
carry out their current duties with maximum effectiveness, and thereby contribute to the
achievement of agreed objectives;
b) To help individuals or groups of staff meet the demands placed on them by organizational
change and development;
c) To help individuals develop skills and/or gain qualifications, which will contribute to the
development of their work and equip them for their future career.
2.0 SCOPE
This policy applies to all SFA Foundation staff who have served their contracts for one (1) year
and above.
3.0 ENFORCMENT
This policy shall be enforced by the HR department and supervisors.
4.0 OBJECTIVES
The objectives of staff learning and development objectives are to:
a) Actively support the Foundation’s mission and the achievement of strategic priorities;
b) Develop a learning organization culture that will continuously improve staff skills and
increase the effectiveness and efficiency of the organization;
c) Encourage and enhance professional and career development of staff and to the extent
possible create career opportunities within and outside SFA Foundation;
d) Create an environment that will encourage the development of skills and knowledge of staff
to meet present and anticipated organizational needs. These may be created by the
changing environment, growth, new technologies and shifting priorities;
e) Raise awareness in and provide guidance to individuals and teams on their own work related
and individual development needs in the context of the organizations plans and priorities;
f) To help individual staff acquire knowledge, skills and understanding which will allow them
to carry out their current duties with maximum effectiveness, and thereby contribute to the
achievement of agreed objectives.
5.0 GUIDING PRINCIPLES
a) SFA Foundation shall recruit staff who meet the required educational and professional
requirements for the respective positions;
b) Training shall be supported with a view to improving managerial and technical skills of staff
at all levels in the performance of their duties;
c) SFA Foundation will provide financial support for learning subject to availability of funds;
d) Learning and development of staff is a joint responsibility shared by the individual staff
member, their line manager, HR and management;
Page 2 of 12
e) Staff learning and development needs will be prioritized according to the organization’s
goals and objectives and the needs of the portfolio that the staff member works in;
f) Learning and development programmes should ensure minimal disruption of the employee’s
work and deliverables;
g) The program undertaken must have a direct relation to the work carried out by the staff
member or will enhance the employee’s prospects for advancement within SFA Foundation;
h) Consultants and temporary staff will not be eligible for training support.
6.0 ROLES AND RESPONSIBILITIES
6.1 Executive Management Team (EMT)
The Executive Management Team has the overall responsibility for policy implementation
including participation in the development of training and development strategies and policy,
training and development initiatives and monitoring and evaluation. EMT has the responsibility for
setting the levels of expenditure that can be allocated to training and development.
6.2 Line Managers/Supervisors
Line managers have a key role in the training and development of their staff. They should ensure
that their staff are trained to carry out their present job effectively and receive training to develop
them for future opportunities. This involves:
▪ Identifying training, development and support needs with staff;
▪ Ensuring plans are developed to help meet these needs;
▪ Providing on the job training where possible;
▪ Providing opportunities for personal development, for example by exploring new areas of
work;
▪ Reviewing, monitoring and evaluating development activities and their effectiveness;
▪ Identifying opportunities to practice new skills and demonstrate knowledge (this could include
briefing other staff on specific subject areas);
▪ Monitoring and ensuring effective and fair use of the budget.
6.3 Individual Staff
Each member of staff has a personal responsibility to participate actively in training to enable
them to carry out their work effectively and efficiently. This involves:
▪ Identifying their own training needs and discussing them with their line manager;
▪ Looking for training and development opportunities both on-the-job and more;
▪ Widely, including attendance at conferences, workshops and seminars;
▪ The development and implementation of an agreed personal development plan;
▪ Monitoring and evaluation of the plan and development activities;
▪ Spending personal time on their own self development.
6.4 Human Resources (HR)
The HR department is responsible for:
▪ Monitoring the training and development policy and reporting back to the EMT any issues
arising;
▪ Providing support and advice to managers and staff on the implementation of the policy,
identification and meeting of needs and where possible information about courses and training
resources.
7.0 IDENTIFYING TRAINING & DEVELOPMENT NEEDS
7.1 Recruitment/Induction/Skills gaps
Assessment of the skills and knowledge an employee needs to do their current job successfully
can be made against the job description and person specification. This is normally done
Page 3 of 12
automatically throughout the recruitment process (e.g. using application forms, test results) and
can be explored further during the induction period.
7.2 Performance Management
Training and development needs are usually identified during the performance management
process and a performance development plan agreed. This is to ensure that the employee can
fulfil the requirements of the job as well as ensure they have the skills to complete the objectives
that have been agreed. (See Performance Management guidelines).
7.3 Organizational changes
Organizational changes, for example a new programme, installation of new software or the
introduction of a new process or policy, can come at any time and whenever they do, an analysis
of training needs should be carried out and appropriate training given.
7.4 Organizational objectives
Some training and development needs would be determined by SFA Foundation’s strategic goals.
For example, if SFA Foundation decided, within their IT objectives, that to improve efficiency all
staff had to use their electronic diaries, appropriate training would need to be organized.
8.0 MANDATORY TRAINING
Training courses that are mandatory are outlined below.
▪ Induction of incoming staff;
▪ Security for staff going to medium or high-risk locations;
▪ Recruitment & selection for managers;
▪ Performance management;
▪ Finance for programme managers;
▪ Monitoring and evaluation for all managers;
▪ Automated systems and processes;
▪ People management training for all Managers.
9.0 APPROACHES AND METHODS OF TRAINING AND DEVELOPMENT:
For many staff the greater part of their training will be on the job, however, from time to time it
may be necessary for employees to attend external training events. Having identified a
learning/development/support need, the next step is identifying the most effective way to meet
the need. It is critical that the development need is specific and required learning objectives clearly
defined. Ways to develop knowledge, skills, and aptitude include:
9.1 Internal opportunities/activities;
▪ Attending meetings, seminars, conferences and workshops;
▪ Secondments;
▪ Temporary additional responsibilities;
▪ Mentoring;
▪ Coaching/on the job training;
▪ Job rotation/development;
▪ Self-directed learning – e.g. computer based, internet.
9.2 External Training
▪ Training courses;
▪ Professional qualifications;
▪ Information about training courses, seminars and conferences is available from the
programme leads or unit;
Page 4 of 12
▪ HR can assist in selecting appropriate courses and may be able to provide reviews of external
training through annual training calendar.
9.3 Sharing learning/experiences
In the interests of cost effectiveness and sharing learning, if possible, there should be a
commitment and arrangements made to share the learning particularly from the external training.
This to include;
▪ A briefing session/presentation oral or written on the key aspects of training;
▪ Sharing of ideas, the training may have raised;
▪ Running a mini in-house training session;
▪ Sharing handouts and guidance links.
9.4 Self-Development
▪ Distance learning
▪ Training and development programmes
▪ Professional membership
▪ Membership of external bodies
10.0 TRAINING BUDGET
The SFA Foundation training budget is calculated on the basis of a % per person per year. Each
functional head is responsible for the total budget for their department and ensuring that the
budget is used fairly and appropriately. Some of the budget may be contributed to organizational
wide training.
Requests for funding must be agreed in the first instance with the line manager. The level of
financial support SFA Foundation will provide for any training or development event is
discretionary and will be prioritized taking into consideration the following;
▪ Relevance of the event to the individuals current job description;
▪ Perceived added value to the team/department;
▪ Priority against organizational need and planned activities;
▪ Cost, method and appropriateness of the event;
▪ Previous funded opportunities;
▪ Time necessary.
11.0 TRAINING RECORDS
A training record for each member of staff will be kept centrally by the HR department. Therefore,
line managers must ensure that an update on any training or development that has taken place
is shared with the department.
Professionals who are subject to Continuing Professional Development (CPD) requirements,
must maintain their own CPD record for the purposes of budgeting and planning.
12.0 ASSISTANCE FOR FURTHER OR HIGHER EDUCATION (DIPLOMA, DEGREE,
MASTERS, PHD)
SFA Foundation EMT will consider requests for assistance towards further education course fees
and approved professional qualification course fees, providing that there is a written development
plan that fits in with the organizational aims. The following guidelines are set out for use by
management:
Page 5 of 12
12.1 Authorization
Any staff member who wishes to pursue a course to further their expertise skills should complete
an application form (Appendix-1) and give it to their line manager and functional head for the
department, this should be copied to the Head of HR. The request should include;
▪ Details of a development plan that is linked to the departments plan;
▪ Details of the course of study;
▪ Cost;
▪ Duration
▪ Day release/distance learning;
▪ Reasons for wishing to pursue the course of study;
▪ How it will benefit the individual and department;
▪ How it is likely to impact the rest of the department/team.
The functional head in conjunction with EMT will be responsible for making a decision within the
context of the department plan, the organizational objectives and the available budget. Where a
course of study is approved, the individual will be reimbursed for up to 50% of the cost of tuition
fees and examination fees. Payment of fees for resits is to be paid by the employee themselves.
12.2 Study Leave
Study Leave will be granted as per the SFA Foundation Human Resource Policy and Procedures
Manual staff handbook policy for those needing to take examinations. Study leave dates need to
be agreed in advance by the line manager who will need to plan for a reallocation of work during
any absence.
12.3 Repayment/Bonding
If an individual obtains a professional qualification or any further education qualification and
subsequently leaves SFA Foundation on their own accord within a specific period after
completion, the following repayment of SFA Foundation financial assistance will be applied:
Resignation after completion of training % of training cost to be refunded
Less than 6 months 100%
6-12 months 70%
13-18 months 50%
19 months – 2 years 25%
The same rule above on the bonding will apply if an individual leaves SFA Foundation before
completing the course of study where SFA Foundation has sponsored and paid for the course.
However, if the individual is made redundant or contract not renewed, this rule will not apply.
An external study course application form (Appendix-2) will need to be obtained from the HR
Department and a signed copy returned to them before a course of study starts.
13.0 MONITORING AND EVALUATION
All internal courses will be evaluated at the end of each course when participants are asked to
complete an immediate reaction questionnaire.
Following attendance at an external event, staff are required to complete a training evaluation
form (Appendix-3) and return it to HR. This enables the HR Manager to monitor the quality of
external events and ensure SFA Foundation gets value for money.
Page 6 of 12
Other means of evaluating training and development include;
▪ Examinations and practical tests, possibly both before and after training
▪ Discussions about the effectiveness of the training/development, particularly after one-to-one
coaching or mentoring
▪ Line managers assessment of enhancement of skills/knowledge and overall performance as
well as changes in behaviour.
The Head of HR will carry out six monthly reviews of training expenditure and recommend
organizational training and/or development in accordance with performance development plans.
