1.0 PURPOSE
Contemporary organizational workplaces, environments, hierarchical and interpersonal
relationships maybe deliberately or inadvertently laden with subtle and unconscious bias,
norms, cultures, policies, systems, processes and business practices which may harm or
abuse employees, research participants, disadvantaged groups or minorities or groups with
special needs and communities.
Such harm and abuse include discrimination, bullying, sexual harassment and all other forms
of harassment. In line with the International Development Research Funders Statement of
Safeguarding, the Science for Africa Foundation (SFA Foundation) is committed to
supporting the development of the highest standards in organizational culture, systems and
practices required to prevent and tackle all forms and incidents of harm and abuse in all its
programmes, internal and external business interactions and practices.
2.0 SCOPE
This policy is applicable to SFA Foundation employees, representatives and institutions
managing SFA Foundation grants.
3.0 DEFINITION
Safeguarding is the process of protecting individuals from abuse or neglect, enabling them to
maintain control over their lives and make informed choices without coercion. It involves
empowering individuals at risk, consulting them before taking action unless someone lacks
the capacity to make a decision, or their mental health poses a risk to their own or someone
else’s safety, in which case, always acting in his or her best interest.
3.1 Forms of Abuse
Abuse can take many forms and the circumstances of the individual must always be
considered. It may consist of a single act or repeated acts. The following is a list of examples
of the different types of abuse which may affect an individual at risk:
a) Physical- includes, but is not limited to, hitting, slapping, pushing, kicking, misuse of
medication, unlawful or inappropriate restraint and inappropriate physical sanctions.
b) Sexual – in unwanted sexual activity or behaviour that happens without consent or
understanding.
c) Psychological – is emotional abuse which causes distress and can be verbal and nonverbal.
d) Financial and material – includes theft, fraud, exploitation and pressure in connection to
wills, property, inheritance and financial transactions, or inciting an individual at risk to do
any of these things on another individual’s behalf; it may also involve the misuse or
misappropriation of property, possessions and benefits of an individual.
e) Discriminatory – includes abuse based on an individual’s race, gender, disability, faith,
sexual orientation or age; and other forms of harassment, slurs or similar treatmentor hate
crime/incident.
4.0 ENFORCEMENT OF POLICY
Safeguarding individuals is everyone’s responsibility and failure to act on concerns relating to
an individual risk is not an option.
SFA Foundation Managers, and ultimately Directors or their equivalent, hold overall
accountability for its implementation. All SFA Foundation staff, grantees and other
representatives of SFA Foundation are required to adhere to this policy and SFA Foundation
code of conduct at all times.
All SFA Foundation employees are obliged to report any suspicions of abuse. Failure to report
to a relevant person is a breach to SFA Foundation policy and could lead to disciplinary action
being taken.
