harm or abuse occurs within SFA Foundation, its partners and within the research
community on the continent, and to continuously raise safeguarding standards across the
international and pan-African research sector, to ensure people are safe and protected
wherever they are located.
n) As part of our commitments to Safeguarding, SFA Foundation recognises the importance
of organisational culture and accountability in creating a safe and supportive organisation
for our staff, partners, and all stakeholders with whom we work. To this end, SFA
Foundation ensures that:-
▪ All staff are continuously improving HR policies and practices to ensure we are
promoting the values and culture that support our vision and mission.
▪ We attract new employees, Board members, consultants, volunteers, interns, and
contractors who demonstrate the culture and behaviours that promote and reinforce
our safeguarding culture, gender equality & diversity and safe workplace, free from
harm.
6.0 PROCEDURE
SFA Foundation is committed to responding to all complaints and concerns of abuse. SFA
Foundation will internally constitutes a safeguarding team to carry out investigations and
delivering support to the abused individuals.
6.1 Incident Reporting
Anyone can raise a concern or make a complaint to SFA Foundation about something they
have experienced or witnessed. ‘
For internal constituents, this can be done in writing or verbally through the Human Resources
department, which is the focal point for safeguarding or via the whistle blowing channels of
communication.
External constituents who work with SFA Foundation (including the grantees) can also raise
a concern without fear of retribution through the respective programme managers or via the
whistle blowing platform.
6.1.1 Management Reports
The Head of Human Resources or designate shall compile an aggregated anonymised report
of all incidences reported within the quarter for the SFA Foundation Executive Management
Team (EMT) for noting. The reports will provide insights into the type of report, status of
investigations and actions taken, and any other necessary details. Any incidences not closed
in the previous quarter will be tracked along with new cases in each current reporting cycle
6.2 Procedure for Handling Complaints
When a complaint or concern has been raised, it must be referred within 24 hours to the SFA
Foundation safeguarding committee, which will be constituted by the Head of Human
Resources or the Programme Manager receiving the complaint or concern.
Page 4 of 4
Internal Response
Within 72 hours of receiving a complaint or concern, SFA Foundation shall convene a case
conference. An email shall be sent to the complainant if known, to acknowledge the complaint
in writing as soon as possible. SFA Foundation may refer suspected cases of vulnerable
individual abuse to local statutory authorities where possible.
6.3 Investigation
The process of addressing complaints, grievance and dispute is outlined in SFA Foundation’s
Disciplinary Policy and Grievance Procedure policy.
Within seven (7) calendar days of the receipt of a formal complaint, the Department Head will
initiate an investigation, of the facts and circumstances of the alleged incident. In such
investigation, the Department Head seeks to determine that:
a) the incidents described in the complaint cannot be dismissed as incredible on their face, and;
b) the incidents as described would constitute a violation of SFA Foundation policy.
At the conclusion of this review the Department Head prepares a report which either calls for a
formal hearing or dismisses the complaint. While there is no set time in which an investigation must
be completed, the Department Head will attempt to conclude it as promptly as possible. The report
will be sent to the complainant, the Foundation employee against whom the grievance was brought,
and the Head of Human Resources. A good faith effort shall be made to assure that this report is
treated confidentially;
6.4 Appeal
a) An employee who is not satisfied with the decision should write to the Head of Human
Resources indicating this and await a decision;
b) An employee who further not satisfied with the decision may appeal for hearing with the
Executive Director.
6.5 Onboarding New Staff
Safe recruitment is important to ensure persons who best reflect the values of SFA Foundation
and principles on Safeguarding are onboarded into the organisation.
6.5.1 Safeguarding on job advertisements
The HR department shall include information about safeguarding commitments in all job
advertisements on SFA Foundation websites, notice boards and recruitment websites.
6.5.2 Safeguarding on references
When recruiting staff, volunteers, board members and consultants it is imperative to ensure
that SFA Foundation receives satisfactory reference requests for successful candidates.
Offers of employment should not be confirmed until all checks are in place and hiring staff are
satisfied that the references received meet SFA Foundation’s standards and requirements. A
sample of the reference check template is provided here as Annex-1.
6.6 Training
All SFA Foundation staff and other representatives must receive training on Safeguarding
Individuals commensurate with their role. This training will be carried out by specialists on
regular basis and will include information about SFA foundations policy positions, reporting
and investigation procedures, and how to embed Safeguarding across the organization.
6.7 Review of the Policy
This policy shall be reviewed annually commencing January 1, 2023.
