INTRODUCTION
Science for Africa (SFA) Foundation is desirous to employ the best practices within the
Procurement Unit. The goal of the SFA Foundation Procurement Policy manual is to ensure
that best value is achieved when procuring goods, services and works while at the same
time supporting SFA Foundation operations and mission.
This Manual governs the procurement of all goods, services and works. It also governs the
standards of conduct for all SFA Foundation personnel involved in the procurement process.
About SFA Foundation
The Science for Africa (SFA) Foundation is a non-profit, pan-African institution, that aims to
support, strengthen and promote science and innovation in Africa for the benefit of all
Africans. The SFA Foundation serves the African research ecosystem by funding excellent
research and innovative ideas and building and reinforcing environments that are conducive
for scientists to thrive and produce quality research that impacts development.
Enforcement of the Manual
The SFA Foundation Procurement Officer, has the primary responsibility to ensure the
acquisition, supply/delivery as well as the disposal of goods and services in the most costeffective, timely, expeditious and efficient method.
1.0 PURPOSE OF THE PROCUREMENT GUIDELINES AND MANUAL
The overall purpose of this manual is to provide a cohesive framework that will govern the
procurement of various goods, works and services by the organization. The manual also
seeks to provide guidance to SFA Foundation staff and the wider network of funders and
partner institutions and suppliers of goods and services, on issues pertaining to procurement
within SFA Foundation, with specific reference to the applicable rules, policies and
procedures under various circumstances.
The Following core concept shall apply:
a) Procurement shall be undertaken in transparent and fair manner;
b) Procurement shall be carried out using competition to the maximumextent;
c) Selection of vendor will be done through best value for money (efficiency, effectiveness,
equity and economical methodology;
d) Staff who procure goods and services will not have perceived or actual conflict of
interest with suppliers;
e) SFA Foundation has zero tolerance to fraudulent procurement practices such as bribes,
kickbacks, price collusion and other unethical behaviors;
f) Selection of vendor, goods, works and services should be properlydocumented;
Page 2 of 39
g) In cases where funding partner require procurement procedures different from those
outlined in this manual, SFA Foundation will seek waiver to follow its own guidelines,
but where such waiver is not granted, the funder’s guidelines shallapply.
2.0 SCOPE
This manual covers:-
a) Guidelines, procedures and methods applied in the procurement process for SFA
Foundation goods services and works;
b) Roles, responsibilities and code of ethics applied in the procurement process for SFA
Foundation goods, services and works;
c) Procedures and methods applied in the disposal of unserviceable or obsolete assets
However, procurement must follow the funding partner procurement requirements.
3.0 DEFINITIONS
For the purposes of this document, the following definitions shall apply:
Budget Holder
The individual responsible for managing and approving budgeted expenditures for a specific
project.
Goods
Are defined as property that have a monetary value and to which, after purchase, The SFA
Foundation retains legal title for a period of time and uses such goods in its operations and
activities.
Invoice (or bill)
A commercial document issued by a seller to the buyer, indicating the products, quantities,
and agreed prices for products or services the seller has provided the buyer. An invoice
indicates the buyer must pay the seller, according to the payment terms.
Local Purchase Order (LPO)
This is an official document (signed and stamped on letterhead) requesting specific items or
service be provided at the quoted price.
Procurement Committee (PC)
Group comprised of recommended staff including a representative from finance and
operations, programmes and procurement and user department.
Page 3 of 39
Procurement Officer (PO)
The person who is responsible for ensuring good practice in procurement. This is the officer
who co-ordinates the supplier’s selections.
Purchase Request (PR)
The purchase request is the initial document that defines the goods and services required.
The purchase request communicates such items as quantity, description, price, budget
codes and approvals needed in order to initiate the procurement process. The PR is
prepared by the requesting party and approved prior to submission to the procurement unit.
Services
Are defined as useful activities that are performed by individuals or companies for The SFA
Foundation that that is intangible in nature.
Supplier
Any person or entity external to the organization, which offers goods or services required by
the organization.
User Unit
This is the Unit, (office, department or section) that requests for the goods and the service.
