4.0 POLICY STATEMENT
4.1 Procurement Objectives
4.1.1 To carry out procurement in a manner that economy and efficiency is maximized,
promote competition and ensure that all bidders are treated fairly;
4.1.2 To ensure timely delivery of goods, works and services to the satisfaction of the user
departments;
4.1.3 To promote procurement professionalism and adherence to the professional ethics;
4.1.4 To measure vendor performance periodically to ensure timelines are met and promote
mutual partnership;
4.1.5 To ensure that the procurement of goods, works and services is carried out in a
transparent and accountable manner;
4.1.6 To ensure timely procurement of quality goods, services, works and
4.1.7 To ensure that procurement planning is done annually as part of the budget making
process to avoid ad hoc purchases.
4.2 Procurement Standards
4.2.1 All SFA Foundation procurement of goods, works and services will conform to policies
and procedures, funding partner requirements, and host country laws as applicable.
All SFA Foundation staff should comply with the policy that includes conflict of interest
that governs the performance of employees engaged in the selection, award and
administration of procurements activities.
4.2.2 The following are the specific policy statements of SFA Foundation:
a) Clear specifications, evaluation methods and criteria shall be defined before the
start of the procurement process;
b) The decision to award a contract to a vendor shall be based on price (total cost of
ownership for goods) and consideration of other factors such as integrity,
reputation, ability to deliver required procurement on time, records of past
performance, warranty, technical and financial resources, responsiveness to
technical requirements, including hire vs. buy decisions; (price is not the only factor
of consideration;
c) The procurement committee will evaluate, select, add, change information and
discontinue the procurement vendor or consultant based on set criteria;
d) The procurement process shall comply with the authorization policy and shall be
well documented;
e) Technical units or other experts will be involved in the procurement decisionmaking process;
f) To enable the SFA Foundation Procurement Officer meet these obligations
effectively and to help handle purchases in a systematic and organized manner,
all departments at SFA Foundation will plan their requirements sufficiently and
submit approved Purchase Request to the procurement officer asfollows:
• Large value items -at least one month before the need;
• Regular items, between 2 days to 1 week.
4.3 Basic Procurement Principles
4.3.1 SFA Foundation will promote and apply sound procurement principles to achieve the
highest standards in procurement within the Secretariat. The following main principles
underlie proficient procurement;
a) Economy and efficiency to achieve quality, cost effectiveness and timely delivery
in procurement;
b) Promotion of transparency and accountability, providing equitable, fair and open
competition to give all eligible/qualified bidders an opportunity to participate in
the procurement and disposal process;
c) Accountability and promotion of value for money through careful procurement
planning;
d) Observance of ethics in all aspects of procurement and ensuring that the practice
is devoid of actual or perceived malpractice;
Page 5 of 39
e) Strict adherence to the use of appropriate documentation for all the steps of the
complete procurement and disposal cycles, and maintenance of comprehensive
record of all procurement processes.
These principles will be used to guide all decisions pertaining to procurement of goods
and services for the SFA Foundation.
4.4 Processes covered by this Policy
4.4.1 The principles and processes outlined in this manual apply to:
a) Procurement of goods (capital equipment and consumables) and construction
works;
b) Outsourced services such as air travel, security, printing, equipment
maintenance, grounds maintenance, and freight, forwarding and clearing
services, accommodation & outside conference facilities rentals, banking,
insurance, etc;
c) Hire of Consultants.
4.5 Amendment and Exceptions
4.5.1 While this manual serves as a general reference to the SFA Foundation, we recognize
that specific programs funded by certain partners may require adherence to the
funder’s procurement guidelines. In such situations, The SFA Foundation will seek
waiver to follow its own guidelines, but where such waiver is not granted, the funder’s
guidelines shall apply.
4.5.2 In the event that certain issues arise during implementation of procurement which
have not been considered fully in this manual, the Executive Director or equivalent
based on the recommendations of the Procurement Committee will consider and
introduce such modifications and amendments as may berequired. The effect of the
amendment on implementation of the policy shall be reviewed for reporting to the
Board for approval or noting.
4.6 Responsibility and Accountability
4.6.1 To ensure the application of sound procurement practices and mitigation against any
malpractices in the procurement process, there shall be clear separation of duties i.e
separation of authority between procurement initiation, vendor selection, commitment
and receipt of thegoods;
4.6.1 All approvals shall be in writing and no retrospective approvals will be allowed.
Procurement within SFA Foundation shall be carried out within the set guidelines and
by the various committees set up by management to execute these functions.
