5.0 PROCUREMENT PROCESS
The procurement process begins with identification of needs by the user department. Needs
are those items or services that should be procured to help SFA Foundation achieve its
strategic plans and goals. All required items must be budgeted for and their total value is what
is referred to as the "annual procurement plan". The flow chart in Figure-1 below describes
SFA Foundation procurement process.
Figure 1: SFA Foundation Procurement Process
5.1 Procurement Planning
5.1.1 Sound planning and co-ordination of procurement is an important basis for an
economic and efficient procurement. The User department(s) shall prepare
departmental procurement plan(s) (Annex-1) at the beginning of each financial year.
This template shall be submitted to the procurement unit for consolidation (Annex-2).
This shall include:
a) Description of the item;
b) Quantity;
c) Procurement method;
d) Unit price;
e) Total cost;
f) Time.
Page 7 of 39
5.2 Purchase Requisition
5.2.1 Purchase of goods works, and services shall be effected through purchase
requisitions and in accordance with approved procurement plans and this shall be
done from the Procurement System;
5.2.1 A User department with a need shall ensure requisition[s] is raised, checked and
approved by budget holder and ensure approved budget is available;
5.2.2 The User department shall give clear Specifications/ Terms of References/ Scope of
Service/ Bills of quantities of the need to be acquired;
5.2.3 Purchase requisition(s) shall be done on the SFA Foundation procurement system as
per the standard request form (Annex-3);
5.2.4 All approved purchase requisition forms shall be received by the Procurement Officer
for action through the procurement system.
5.3 Initiating the Procurement Process
5.3.1 Procurement will be initiated after the need for an item, service or works has been
identified and the same has been certified by the budget holder/Head of Department;
5.3.2 Users have the responsibility of drawing up the correct specifications of their
procurement needs before forwarding them to the Procurement Officer. If need be,
users may seek the assistance of technical experts in drawing up specifications;
5.3.3 Items should be described in sufficient detail in terms of performance. Specifications
may be presented by one or a combination of thefollowing:
Description
Sample
Drawings
Capacity
Usage
Standards
5.3.4 Once specifications have been drawn up, they shall not be changed without the
involvement of the user;
5.3.5 The responsibility for preparing the specifications is shared by the user department
and technical departments and coordinated by the Procurement Officer;
5.3.6 All procurement work shall be carried out by the designated procurement officer after
the user has drawn up specifications.
5.4 Invitation of Bids
Depending on the nature and value of the procurement requirement, the procurement officer
will request for bids using the appropriate procurementmethod.
5.5 Opening of bids
After the closing date, the bids will be opened by the PO or procurement committee
depending on the procurement method and the process captured in the Procurement
Committee (PC) report.
5.6 Evaluation of bids
An evaluation is conducted by the ad hoc Procurement and Evaluation Committee (PEC) or
Procurement Committee (PC) using the criteria stipulated in the bidding documents. No other
criteria shall be introduced by the ad hoc Procurement Evaluation Committee or Procurement
Committee.
5.7 Approval
The report of the ad hoc PEC or PC with clear recommendation and justification shall be
submitted to the Head of Finance or equivalent for review and submission to the Executive
Director or equivalent for approval. Once approved, financial negotiations may be held with
the recommended firm, before award of the contract.
5.7.1 Award of the contract
The PO shall notify the successful bidder of the award of the contract. For high-value
procurement, the notification shall be in writing whereas, for low procurement, an
email can suffice. The successful bidder shall be required to return a copy as a way
of acceptance of the offer.
Page 8 of 39
5.7.2 Debriefing of Suppliers
The PO shall communicate the regret of the procurement decision to unsuccessful
suppliers, and this shall be in writing. The PO shall prepare detailed written debriefs
which are reviewed and approved by the HoFG. The debriefs for sealed bid/ Tender
shall be in writing.
5.8 Award of the Contract
5.8.1 Standstill period and handling of appeals
The SFA Foundation shall provide for a standstill period of 5 working days to allow
unsuccessful suppliers to request additional feedback and/or raise an appeal. The
contract must not be awarded until the standstill period has been successfully
completed without challenge.
5.8.2 Negotiation Meeting
Negotiations may be conducted with the successful supplier after the expiry of the
standstill period. Such negotiations may be directed to any aspect of the procurement,
including price, quantity, due diligence recommendations and the terms of the
Contract. If however, during and/or after the negotiations it becomes apparent that it
is impossible to contract the successful supplier, the SFA Foundation may contact the
second-best supplier and make an offer. If the latter supplier adheres to the offer,
negotiations shall be conducted. In the case where the second-best supplier is
unavailable to take up the assignment, SFA shall consider whether there is a need to
re-issue the solicitation documents
5.8.3 Issue of contract
Following the award decision, expiry of the standstill period, and acceptance of the
offer, the contract/LPO shall be awarded, which shall detail the terms of reference/
specifications/ scope of service/ bills of quantities, payment terms, timelines, and
delivery schedules, reporting requirements, applicable law and settlement of disputes,
and any other pertinent information. The standard contract provided by the selected
company may be used as long as it includes all the standard clauses as approved by
the SFA Foundation legal department.
Contracts for services should not be longer than three years except in cases where
the contractor has made a substantial investment that is hard to withdraw, a longer
contract may be considered but the market should be tested regularly and carefully,
and performance review conducted.
The PO shall prepare a contract for review by the user, legal team and HoFG before
approval by the ED. The contract will be comprised of the contract template, terms,
and conditions, solicitation documents, ToR), final technical and commercial
proposals, and the final negotiated budget. Once the Contract has been approved by
the ED, the PO shall send a copy to the supplier for execution.
5.8.4 Amendments of the contract
Amendment of Contract is necessary when there is a need to change material aspects
of the Contract, such as extension of the duration of the Contract, or modification of
the services to be delivered. Contracts shall be amended by use of an addendum.
Each addendum shall identify the Contract to which it refers by number, subject and
date. The nature of the amendment shall be clearly described and include a statement
that all other terms contract, and conditions of the Contract shall remain unchanged.
The procedures for signing an amendment are the same as those for the original
Contract. Amendments shall be submitted to the Legal team and Head of finance for
review before approval by the ED. Contracts shall not be increased or extended as a
means for unduly avoiding competitive solicitation for the requirement. They shall only
be amended to reflect a development in the contractual arrangement, such as a
change in prices or other material change in circumstances.
5.8.5 Payments
Page 9 of 39
All payments for contracts shall be subject to set deliverables that shall be tied to
specific milestones in the contract. The SFA Foundation shall make payments in
accordance with the terms and conditions of the contract. Progress payments based
on deliverables /milestones achieved shall be the preferred payment method.
5.8.6 Contract tracker
The procurement Officer shall maintain a record of all the contracts issued to
suppliers on the contract tracker register. The contract register shall detail name of
the supplier, description of the contract, duration, the value, CI, the contract status,
payment terms and any other relevant information
5.9 Contract Management
The contract shall set out:
a) The deliverables/milestones, phasing and payments agreed at the contract inception
meeting and stated in the TOR and contract;
b) The named contact points from SFA Foundation;
c) The form and frequency of contract management meetings;
d) The way relevant milestones will be measured and reported.
5.10 Contract Administration
