7.0 PROCUREMENT METHODS
The following are the methods of procurement that The SFA Foundation will employ in
procurement of Goods and services for both local and international procurement. The use of
each method will be guided by what is most appropriate considering the value (thresholds)
and thecomplexity.
7.1 Direct Procurement
7.1.1 For goods, services, works and consultancies below US$ 500, purchases will be
made from the approved vendor(s) list without obtaining competitive quotes. A memo
or email from the User department is sufficient. The PO will request for quotation and
raise a Local Purchase Order (LPO) from the Procurement system;
7.1.2 Procurement staff shall ensure all suppliers are accorded fair treatment by rotating
award to all the pre-qualified suppliers. Procurement officer shall be required to carry
out market survey as well as prices analysis to ensure items are not procured above
market prevailing prices.
7.2 Request for Quotations (RFQ)
7.2.1 For goods, services and consultancies of US$ 501- 1500, purchases are made through
competitive quotation process. The minimum number of quotations to be obtained
from vendors shall be three (3). In instances where only two vendors are available to
provide quotations, the Procurement Officer shall document the reason. In the
instances where only one vendor is available, a sole source justification form must be
filled. The Procurement officer can do the analysis and proceed with the award;
7.2.2 For goods, services and consultancies of US$ 1501- 5000, purchases are made
through competitive quotation process as stated above but the user department shall
be involved in the analysis and theaward;
7.2.3 For goods, services and consultancies of US$ 5001- 50000, purchases are made
through competitive quotation process as stipulated above. The PC shall conduct the
opening and the analysis of the quotations and prepare a report on the same;
7.2.4 In compliance with effective competition, the Procurement Officer shall send RFQ to
all suppliers at the same time. If less than three quotations are received, a second
round of request may be made if those received do not meet the requirements.
Otherwise, evaluation shall be done where the offer complies with the requirements
as indicated in the RFQ document. RFQ/RFQ must be in writing;
7.2.5 Procurement shall prepare Summary Bids Analysis (SBA). If a vendor was requested
to quote and never responded, the procurement officer shall include the name of the
vendor and indicate ‘No Response Received’;
7.2.6 The PO shall forward the SBA and award recommendations to the budget holder/User
department for review. This should also be done for procurements whose total cost
exceeds the estimated budget;
7.2.7 The signed SBA shall be forwarded to the HFG for approval.
7.3 Sealed Bids (Tender Method)
7.3.1 For goods, services, works or consultancies above US$ 50,001. Sealed quotations
are solicited through public advertisement or from approved vendors list in writing.
The formal advertisement and letters must include the following:
7.3.2 Specifications of the goods, service, works or Consultancies;
a) Tender number;
b) Tender closing time and date;
c) Delivery date;
d) Evaluation Criteria;
e) Payment schedule.
7.3.3 Where approved vendors are invited to bid, the following shallapply:
a) Bids shall be submitted in through the procurement system and should only be
opened after the closing time and date;
b) Bidders shall not be permitted to alter their bids after the deadline for receipt of
