7.4 Single Sourcing
This procedure shall enable SFA Foundation to enter into negotiations with one or more
suppliers (with or without running a competition) when a decision has been taken that this is
the appropriate selection method. It is normally only applied where competition is not viable
(where a competition has failed to identify an acceptable tender, there is only one supplier
available or uniquely placed to provide the services or goods, or there is a case of extreme
urgency (not poor planning). Having used a subcontractor or supplier in the past for similar
work is not a valid Single Source justification. The requester shall fill in the non-competitive
single source document for approval by the ED or any Designated authority (refer to Annex
6).
7.5 Requests for Proposal (RFP)
The RFP is a prospectus inviting consultants to apply for work on a specific project. It outlines
all the work and products required of a consultant and provides a means for evaluating the
ability of various consultants to perform the required services. The RFP process is the same
as that of direct procurement, RFQ and sealed bids/tender method for procurement of goods,
non-consultancy services and work, however, the method of selection will be different. SFA
Foundation shall use this RFP process when selecting consultants.
7.5.1 RFP Invitation
The RFP shall be sent to at least three (3) consultants who are qualified to perform
the work. In any event, the process must be open, and anyone wishing to respond to
the RFP shall be given the opportunity. Consultants should be contacted to assure their
interest in submitting a proposal. Once this is done, the RFP shall be issued to all
those who have indicated interest in responding;
7.5.2 Responding to the RFP
Consultants will be allowed sufficient time to respond to the RFP. The length of time
can vary depending on the nature of the proposal. The minimum time shall be 14 days
Page 18 of 39
and maximum 21 days;
7.5.3 Pre-Submission Conference
This may be conducted, and the purpose will be to discuss and clarify the project,
scope of work/service, TOR and other details such as insurance requirements, the
budget, billing procedures etc;
7.5.4 Deadline for Submission
As a rule, the deadline for receipt of proposals should be within two to three weeks
after the pre-submission conference is held. Any extension for to the submission
deadline must be approved and communicated using the same medium of
advertisement.
7.6 Evaluation Criteria
Proposals will generally be evaluated on the technical and financial criteria. The set
committee shall review the technical capabilities before reviewing the financial proposal.
7.6.1 Evaluation Procedures
Potential bidders shall be subjected to desk-based review by the PC. The first five (5)
bidders who shall score a minimum of 70% shall be subjected to further technical
evaluation through interviews and on a set criterion. The recommendations for the
award shall be based on the combined Technical (interview scores) and financial
scores.
Depending on the requirements and the scope of the RFP, the technical weight shall
not exceed 80% of the total weight whereas the financial weight shall not exceed
20% of the total weight.
The final weighted score for each tenderer shall be calculated in accordance with the
equation below:-
Final Score = TS x T% + FS x F%, where T% + F% shall always be equal to 100%.
- Final Score (FS) is the total combined scores of technical and financial scores;
- T% is the weighting given to the technical proposal;
- TS is the overall technical scores (Interview)
- F% is the weighting given to the financial proposal
- T% shall be 80% and F% shall be 20% respectively.
7.6.2 Consensus meeting
After the technical and financial evaluations are concluded, the PO shall combine the
scores and rank the bidders. A consensus meeting will be held by the PC to jointly
discuss and reach a consensus on the responsiveness of the bids received to the
requirements of the solicitation documents as well as interview outcome. The meeting
will also review the process to ensure transparency, work through any anomalies, and
to ensure that the final decision is based on a supporting narrative that will stand up
to external scrutiny. The tender shall be awarded to the highest-ranking and most
responsive bidder based on the outcome of the consensus meeting. This shall be
documented in the selection report.
7.6.3 Quality of Proposal
The proposal should be indicative of the type of work a consultant will do and capture
clear methodologies and workplans. If a proposal is drawn up carefully and
thoroughly, it is an indication the consultant concerned about doing a goodjob;
7.6.3.1 Track Record/ Experience
The consultant should have completed similar works or services (copies of these
should be available for review if requested), preferably recently; Where a firm
participates in bidding, the experience provided should be that of the firm and not for
the individual staff.
7.6.3.2 Time
The consultant must have the ability to complete work within the requested time frame.
