7.7 Information to be included in the RFP
7.7.1 Overall Scope of RFP
RFPs should be accompanied by a cover letter introducing the project. Certain
information about the project, in addition to the description of services, must be
transmitted. This can be included within the RFP itself, within the cover letter, or a
combination of both. The consultant must be informed of the following:
a) The type of professional service or product desired (e.g. market analysis,
feasibility study, graphic design and logos or promotional brochureetc.);
b) The date proposals are due; whether there will be a mandatory pre-submission
meeting, and if so, where and when; expected commencement of work and time
performance;
c) If appropriate, a map of the target area should be included with theRFP;
d) An individual to whom the consultant can address questions prior tosubmission;
e) The number of copies of the proposal required and where they should besent;
f) Deadlines for receipt of proposals.
7.7.2 Specific RFP Format (refer to annex 11)
When sending the RFP to the consultant, the following must be included:
a) Title Sheet: The title sheet should include the client's name, an indication of what
the RFP will be used for and the deadline for submitting responses;
b) Introduction: The introduction briefly describes the project for which a consultant
will be hired. It should give a concise background or history of the project
describing its major components;
c) Objectives: Define objectives and purposes of project as specifically aspossible;
d) Scope of Services: Identify the specific tasks that must be performed in order to
achieve your stated objectives. Once the consultant is hired, the scope of services
becomes the work guidelines. The scope of services should describe the parties
involved, phasing (if any), expenses to be incurred and the time schedule. It
should clearly describe the relationship of the consultant's work to the project, who
will use the work product, the specific audience to be addressed, and, especially,
the purpose of the consultant’s work. The client should be clearly identified,
including a brief account of the SFA Foundation’s purpose, general scope of
activity, and specific role in the project.
7.8 Consultant’s Proposal
The consultant's response to the RFP should include the following:
7.8.1 Cover Letter
This should be a very brief introduction to the project. It should act only as an
introduction to the more in-depth sections discussed later in the proposal;
7.8.2 Introduction/Summary of Work
The most salient features of the proposal should be addressed in this section. The
introduction or summary should cover all the major areas that the consultant will cover
in his/her proposal.
