7.8.3 Methodology and approach
This is where the consultant's proposal should address the RFP in detail. There
should be a plan describing the consultant's approach to meeting each of the needs
outlined in the RFP. The scope of services may include such items as maps, raw data,
brief market or planning analysis, implementing strategies or preliminary drawings,
designs orsketches.
7.8.4 Proposed Timetable and Phasing
This section should outline all work tasks and approximate completion dates. The
timetable should include at least one mid- project review.
7.8.5 Fee and Manning Schedule
The fee and manning schedule can be described in one of two ways. The consultant
can break down expenses by employee at their respective salary levels or by phases
on a lump sum basis. If they choose to be paid on a lump sum basis, it is suggested
that the bulk of the payment be made at the end of the project, after the work is
satisfactorily completed. Time sheets should be required to back up invoices when
paying hourly. A maximum price for the work should be provided.
7.8.6 Qualifications
A summary of any other project that the consultant has completed which is similar to
the RFP should be included. References and past clients should be identified by
name, position, address and phonenumber.
7.8.7 Project Staffing
A list of key personnel, their resumes and relevant experience. If applicable,
anticipated sub-contractors should be listed with theirresumes.
7.8.8 Final Products or Publications
The consultant's proposal should outline what specific data will be included in the
final study. This could include a listing of charts, graphs, maps, strategies, and/or
description of the final report. It should respond directly to the products specified in
the RFP.
7.9 Methods of Selection of Consultants
7.9.1 Individual Consultants Selection Method
Individual consultants are engaged on assignments for which professional
qualifications and experience at individual level are the only key requirements. This is
where an activity requires the services of an individual and not collective responsibility.
Individual consultants may be hired for a specific task with defined terms of reference
(TOR) or to act as short-term project staff with specific job descriptions. The following
shall be put in consideration when using RFP:
a) The user department shall submit a purchase requisition (PR) with the TOR,
budget and/or cost estimates as per the procurement plan;
b) The advert shall be circulated widely depending on the threshold and shall remain
open for a minimum of 14 days and maximum of 21 days;
c) Technical proposals and financial proposals shall be submitted separately;
d) Schedule of payments and payment procedures shall be agreed upon during
negotiations with the individual consultant;
e) An advance payment may be considered for some specific tasks and shall not
exceed 30% of the contract value;
