10.0 PROCUREMENT CODE OF ETHICS
As funds of SFA Foundation are entrusted to the organization by its funders and partners and
the public at large, it is imperative that all transactions committing SFA Foundation are carried
out to the highest degree of public trust and should be conducted under the best standards.
10.1 Ethics & Conflict of Interest
10.1.1 It is the policy of SFA Foundation that every person that causes or is responsible for
procurement decision within the organization arrives at that decision in a fair and
transparent manner and that all procurement activities are executed ethically.
10.1.2 Each action taken in the procurement process shall be for the benefit of SFA
Foundation and not for personal gain. This policy covers the conduct of any employee,
involved in SFA Foundation procurement process or decision.
10.1.3 All personnel involved in the procurement process shall sign copy of conflict of interest
and copies kept by the procurement department.
10.2 Ethics
10.2.1 All procurement activities shall be executed consistent with the highest professional,
ethical and moral standards.
10.2.2 Persons involved in procurement function and decisions shall not use their positions
within SFA Foundation for individual gain and must maintain honesty and fairness
while executing their responsibilities.
10.3 Conflict of interest
10.3.1 Any employee or a member of a committee of SFA Foundation who has conflict of
interest with respect to procurement activities or decisions: -
a) Shall declare any interest in the procurement under consideration in writing;
b) Shall not take part in procurement proceedings;
c) Shall not after a procurement contract has been entered into, take part in any
decision relating to the procurement or contract.
10.3.2 All staff involved in procurement in SFA Foundation shall be required to declare that
they will not have conflict of interest by signing the conflict-of-interest declaration
forms.
10.4 Collusion
No SFA Foundation employee or board member shall be allowed to collude or attempt to
collude with any other person:
a) To make any proposed price higher than otherwise could have been thecase;
b) To influence or to have other person refrain from submitting a tender, proposal or
quotation;
c) To withdraw or alter the contents of a tender, proposal orquotation;
d) To submit a tender, proposal or quotation with a specified price or with any specified
inclusions or exclusions.
10.5 Fraudulent Practice
No SFA Foundation employee shall be involved in a fraudulent practice in any procurement
proceedings or decisions.
10.6 Corrupt Practice
No SFA Foundation employee shall be involved in any corrupt practice in any procurement
proceedings. No SFA Foundation staff shall be allowed to accept bribes or favors in return of
procurement intelligence. Any staff Involvement in corrupt activities shall be dealt with as
provided in the SFA Foundation HR Manual –disciplinary procedure.
10.7 Disclosure of Procurement information
All information relating to tender or any other procurement activity with suppliers shall be
availed to all potential bidders and no information shall be privy to selected suppliers.
